# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fourier-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] In mathematics (in particular, functional analysis), **convolution** is a mathematical operation on two functions f and g that produces a third function $f*g$ , as the integral of the product of the two functions after one is reflected about the y-axis and shifted.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The term *convolution* refers to both the resulting function and to the process of computing it.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The integral is evaluated for all values of shift, producing the convolution function.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The choice of which function is reflected and shifted before the integral does not change the integral result (see commutativity).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Graphically, it expresses how the 'shape' of one function is modified by the other.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] For complex-valued functions, the cross-correlation operator is the adjoint of the convolution operator.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Convolution has applications that include probability, statistics, acoustics, spectroscopy, signal processing and image processing, computer vision and human vision, geophysics, engineering, physics, and differential equations.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The convolution can be defined for functions on Euclidean space and other groups (as algebraic structures).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] For example, periodic functions, such as the discrete-time Fourier transform, can be defined on a circle and convolved by periodic convolution.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] (See row 18 at DTFT § Properties.) A *discrete convolution* can be defined for functions on the set of integers.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Generalizations of convolution have applications in the field of numerical analysis and numerical linear algebra, and in the design and implementation of finite impulse response filters in signal processing.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Computing the inverse of the convolution operation is known as deconvolution.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The convolution of f and g is written $f*g$ , denoting the operator with the symbol * .
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] It is defined as the integral of the product of the two functions after one is reflected about the y-axis and shifted.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] While the symbol t is used above, it need not represent the time domain.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] At each t , the convolution formula can be described as the area under the function $f(\tau )$ weighted by the function $g(-\tau )$ shifted by the amount t .
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] For the multi-dimensional formulation of convolution, see *domain of definition* (below).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] which has to be interpreted carefully to avoid confusion.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] respectively, the convolution operation $(f*g)(t)$ can be defined as the inverse Laplace transform of the product of $F(s)$ and $G(s)$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Note that $F(s)\cdot G(s)$ is the bilateral Laplace transform of $(f*g)(t)$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] A similar derivation can be done using the unilateral Laplace transform (one-sided Laplace transform).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The convolution operation also describes the output (in terms of the input) of an important class of operations known as *linear time-invariant* (LTI).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] See LTI system theory for a derivation of convolution as the result of LTI constraints.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] In terms of the Fourier transforms of the input and output of an LTI operation, no new frequency components are created.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The existing ones are only modified (amplitude and/or phase).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] In other words, the output transform is the pointwise product of the input transform with a third transform (known as a transfer function).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] See Convolution theorem for a derivation of that property of convolution.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Conversely, convolution can be derived as the inverse Fourier transform of the pointwise product of two Fourier transforms.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] One of the earliest uses of the convolution integral appeared in D'Alembert's derivation of Taylor's theorem in *Recherches sur différents points importants du système du monde,* published in 1754.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] is used by Sylvestre François Lacroix on page 505 of his book entitled *Treatise on differences and series*, which is the last of 3 volumes of the encyclopedic series: *Traité du calcul différentiel et du calcul intégral*, Chez Courcier, Paris, 1797–1800.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Soon thereafter, convolution operations appear in the works of Pierre Simon Laplace, Jean-Baptiste Joseph Fourier, Siméon Denis Poisson, and others.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The term itself did not come into wide use until the 1950s or 1960s.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Prior to that it was sometimes known as *Faltung* (which means *folding* in German), *composition product*, *superposition integral*, and *Carson's integral*.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Yet it appears as early as 1903, though the definition is rather unfamiliar in older uses.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] is a particular case of composition products considered by the Italian mathematician Vito Volterra in 1913.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The summation is called a periodic summation of the function f .
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] When $g_{T}$ is a periodic summation of another function, g , then $f*g_{T}$ is known as a *circular* or *cyclic* convolution of f and g .
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] And if the periodic summation above is replaced by $f_{T}$ , the operation is called a *periodic* convolution of $f_{T}$ and $g_{T}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The convolution of two finite sequences is defined by extending the sequences to finitely supported functions on the set of integers.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] When the sequences are the coefficients of two polynomials, then the coefficients of the ordinary product of the two polynomials are the convolution of the original two sequences.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] This is known as the Cauchy product of the coefficients of the sequences.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The notation $f*_{N}g$ for *cyclic convolution* denotes convolution over the cyclic group of integers modulo *N*.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Circular convolution arises most often in the context of fast convolution with a fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithm.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] In many situations, discrete convolutions can be converted to circular convolutions so that fast transforms with a convolution property can be used to implement the computation.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] For example, convolution of digit sequences is the kernel operation in multiplication of multi-digit numbers, which can therefore be efficiently implemented with transform techniques (Knuth 1997, §4.3.3.C; von zur Gathen & Gerhard 2003, §8.2).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The most common fast convolution algorithms use fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithms via the circular convolution theorem.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Specifically, the circular convolution of two finite-length sequences is found by taking an FFT of each sequence, multiplying pointwise, and then performing an inverse FFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Convolutions of the type defined above are then efficiently implemented using that technique in conjunction with zero-extension and/or discarding portions of the output.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Other fast convolution algorithms, such as the Schönhage–Strassen algorithm or the Mersenne transform, use fast Fourier transforms in other rings.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The Winograd method is used as an alternative to the FFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] It significantly speeds up 1D, 2D, and 3D convolution.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] If one sequence is much longer than the other, zero-extension of the shorter sequence and fast circular convolution is not the most computationally efficient method available.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Instead, decomposing the longer sequence into blocks and convolving each block allows for faster algorithms such as the overlap–save method and overlap–add method.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] A hybrid convolution method that combines block and FIR algorithms allows for a zero input-output latency that is useful for real-time convolution computations.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] and is well-defined only if f and g decay sufficiently rapidly at infinity in order for the integral to exist.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Conditions for the existence of the convolution may be tricky, since a blow-up in g at infinity can be easily offset by sufficiently rapid decay in f.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] If f and g are compactly supported continuous functions, then their convolution exists, and is also compactly supported and continuous (Hörmander 1983, Chapter 1).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] More generally, if either function (say f) is compactly supported and the other is locally integrable, then the convolution *f*∗*g* is well-defined and continuous.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Convolution of f and g is also well defined when both functions are locally square integrable on **R** and supported on an interval of the form [*a*, +∞) (or both supported on [−∞, *a*]).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The convolution of f and g exists if f and g are both Lebesgue integrable functions in *L*1(**R***d*), and in this case *f*∗*g* is also integrable (Stein & Weiss 1971, Theorem 1.3).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] This is a consequence of Tonelli's theorem.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] This is also true for functions in *L*1, under the discrete convolution, or more generally for the convolution on any group.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] In the particular case *p* = 1, this shows that *L*1 is a Banach algebra under the convolution (and equality of the two sides holds if f and g are non-negative almost everywhere).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] More generally, Young's inequality implies that the convolution is a continuous bilinear map between suitable *L**p* spaces.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] so that the convolution is a continuous bilinear mapping from *L**p*×*L**q* to *L**r*.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The Young inequality for convolution is also true in other contexts (circle group, convolution on **Z**).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The optimal value of *B**p*,*q* was discovered in 1975 and independently in 1976, see Brascamp–Lieb inequality.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] In addition to compactly supported functions and integrable functions, functions that have sufficiently rapid decay at infinity can also be convolved.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] An important feature of the convolution is that if *f* and *g* both decay rapidly, then *f*∗*g* also decays rapidly.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] In particular, if *f* and *g* are rapidly decreasing functions, then so is the convolution *f*∗*g*.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Combined with the fact that convolution commutes with differentiation (see #Properties), it follows that the class of Schwartz functions is closed under convolution (Stein & Weiss 1971, Theorem 3.3).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] remains valid in the case where *f* is a distribution, and *g* a compactly supported distribution (Hörmander 1983, §4.2).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] where $A\subset \mathbf {R} ^{d}$ is a measurable set and $1_{A}$ is the indicator function of A .
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] This agrees with the convolution defined above when μ and ν are regarded as distributions, as well as the convolution of L1 functions when μ and ν are absolutely continuous with respect to the Lebesgue measure.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] where the norm is the total variation of a measure.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Because the space of measures of bounded variation is a Banach space, convolution of measures can be treated with standard methods of functional analysis that may not apply for the convolution of distributions.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The convolution defines a product on the linear space of integrable functions.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] This product satisfies the following algebraic properties, which formally mean that the space of integrable functions with the product given by convolution is a commutative associative algebra without identity (Strichartz 1994, §3.3).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Other linear spaces of functions, such as the space of continuous functions of compact support, are closed under the convolution, and so also form commutative associative algebras.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] (i.e., double integrals can be evaluated as iterated integrals in either order).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Proof: This follows from linearity of the integral.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] No algebra of functions possesses an identity for the convolution.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The linear space of compactly supported distributions does, however, admit an identity under the convolution.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The same result holds if *f* and *g* are only assumed to be nonnegative measurable functions, by Tonelli's theorem.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] where ${\frac {d}{dx}}$ is the derivative.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] A particular consequence of this is that the convolution can be viewed as a "smoothing" operation: the convolution of *f* and *g* is differentiable as many times as *f* and *g* are in total.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] These identities hold for example under the condition that *f* and *g* are absolutely integrable and at least one of them has an absolutely integrable (L1) weak derivative, as a consequence of Young's convolution inequality.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] These identities also hold much more broadly in the sense of tempered distributions if one of *f* or *g* is a rapidly decreasing tempered distribution, a compactly supported tempered distribution or a Schwartz function and the other is a tempered distribution.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] On the other hand, two positive integrable and infinitely differentiable functions may have a nowhere continuous convolution.
