[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] If *f* is a Schwartz function, then *τxf* is the convolution with a translated Dirac delta function *τ**x**f* = *f* ∗ *τ**x* *δ*.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] So translation invariance of the convolution of Schwartz functions is a consequence of the associativity of convolution.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Furthermore, under certain conditions, convolution is the most general translation invariant operation.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Thus some translation invariant operations can be represented as convolution.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Convolutions play an important role in the study of time-invariant systems, and especially LTI system theory.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The representing function *g**S* is the impulse response of the transformation *S*.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] A more precise version of the theorem quoted above requires specifying the class of functions on which the convolution is defined, and also requires assuming in addition that *S* must be a continuous linear operator with respect to the appropriate topology.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] It is known, for instance, that every continuous translation invariant continuous linear operator on *L*1 is the convolution with a finite Borel measure.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] More generally, every continuous translation invariant continuous linear operator on *L**p* for 1 ≤ *p* < ∞ is the convolution with a tempered distribution whose Fourier transform is bounded.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] To wit, they are all given by bounded Fourier multipliers.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] In typical cases of interest *G* is a locally compact Hausdorff topological group and λ is a (left-) Haar measure.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] In that case, unless *G* is unimodular, the convolution defined in this way is not the same as ${\textstyle \int f\left(xy^{-1}\right)g(y)\,d\lambda (y)}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Furthermore, the convention is also required for consistency with the definition of the convolution of measures given below.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] However, with a right instead of a left Haar measure, the latter integral is preferred over the former.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] On locally compact abelian groups, a version of the convolution theorem holds: the Fourier transform of a convolution is the pointwise product of the Fourier transforms.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The circle group **T** with the Lebesgue measure is an immediate example.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] By the commutativity property cited above, *T* is normal: *T** *T* = *TT** .
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Also, *T* commutes with the translation operators.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Consider the family *S* of operators consisting of all such convolutions and the translation operators.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Then *S* is a commuting family of normal operators.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] According to spectral theory, there exists an orthonormal basis {*hk*} that simultaneously diagonalizes *S*.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] This characterizes convolutions on the circle.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] which are precisely the characters of **T**.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Each convolution is a compact multiplication operator in this basis.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] This can be viewed as a version of the convolution theorem discussed above.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] A discrete example is a finite cyclic group of order *n*.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Convolution operators are here represented by circulant matrices, and can be diagonalized by the discrete Fourier transform.
