[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] In fact, if *either* measure is absolutely continuous with respect to the Haar measure, then so is their convolution.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] If μ and ν are probability measures on the topological group (**R**,+), then the convolution *μ*∗*ν* is the probability distribution of the sum *X* + *Y* of two independent random variables *X* and *Y* whose respective distributions are μ and ν.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Let (*X*, Δ, ∇, *ε*, *η*) be a bialgebra with comultiplication Δ, multiplication ∇, unit η, and counit *ε*.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The convolution is a product defined on the endomorphism algebra End(*X*) as follows.
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] The convolution appears notably in the definition of Hopf algebras (Kassel 1995, §III.3).
[src:fourier-analysis/convolution] Convolution and related operations are found in many applications in science, engineering and mathematics.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In mathematics, the **discrete Fourier transform** (**DFT**) is a discrete version of the Fourier transform that converts a finite sequence of numbers into another sequence of the same length, representing the amplitude and phase of different frequency components.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In this way, it changes data from a description in terms of sampled values to a description in terms of oscillations.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The inverse discrete Fourier transform reverses this process and recovers the original sequence.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] For data sampled at equally spaced points, the DFT can be understood more precisely as converting between sample values and the coefficients of a trigonometric polynomial that interpolates those values.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] It is therefore a basic tool for numerical work with smooth periodic functions, which can often be approximated well by trigonometric polynomials.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In practice, the DFT is usually computed by efficient fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithms.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The DFT is used in many practical applications of Fourier analysis.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In digital signal processing, the input is often a sampled quantity or signal that varies over time, such as the pressure of a sound wave, a radio signal, or daily temperature readings, sampled over a finite time interval (often defined by a window function).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In image processing, the samples can be the values of pixels along a row or column of a raster image.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The DFT is also used to efficiently solve partial differential equations, and to perform other operations such as convolutions or multiplying large integers.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Since the DFT deals with a finite amount of data, it can be implemented in computers by numerical algorithms or even dedicated hardware.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] These implementations usually employ efficient fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithms; so much so that the terms "FFT" and "DFT" are often used interchangeably.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Prior to its current usage, the "FFT" initialism may have also been used for the ambiguous term "finite Fourier transform".
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The transform is sometimes denoted by the symbol ${\mathcal {F}}$ , as in $\mathbf {X} ={\mathcal {F}}\left\{\mathbf {x} \right\}$ or ${\mathcal {F}}\left(\mathbf {x} \right)$ or ${\mathcal {F}}\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] As a linear transformation on a finite-dimensional vector space, the DFT expression can also be written in terms of a DFT matrix.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] When scaled appropriately, it becomes a unitary matrix, and the DFT can thus be viewed as a transformation from one orthonormal basis to another.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The normalization factor multiplying the DFT and inverse DFT (IDFT), here 1 and ${\tfrac {1}{N}}$ , and the signs of the exponents are the most common conventions.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The only actual requirements of these conventions are that the DFT and IDFT have opposite-sign exponents and that the product of their normalization factors be ${\tfrac {1}{N}}.$ An uncommon normalization of ${\sqrt {\tfrac {1}{N}}}$ for both the DFT and IDFT makes the transform-pair unitary.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Using the standard definition of the DFT omits the sampling interval (or sampling distance) $\Delta t$ in cases where the index corresponds to time via $n\Delta t=t$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Most software libraries compute the unscaled DFT coefficients $X_{k}$ , including their corresponding FFT implementations.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The scaled coefficients can therefore be obtained as ${\tilde {X}}_{k}=\Delta t\cdot X_{k}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] When applying the DFT to physical data, the sampling interval $\Delta t$ (or equivalently $\Delta f$ ) is an essential part of the signal definition.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Including the sampling interval ensures correct amplitude, energy, and frequency interpretation, particularly when combining or comparing data from different sources.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The DFT can be regarded as transforming a finite sequence of equally-spaced samples of a function into a same-length sequence of equally-spaced samples of the discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT), which is a complex-valued function of frequency.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The interval at which the DTFT is sampled is the reciprocal of the duration of the input sequence.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] An inverse DFT (IDFT) is a Fourier series, using the DTFT samples as coefficients of complex sinusoids at the corresponding DTFT frequencies.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] It has the same sample-values as the original input sequence.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The DFT is therefore said to be a frequency domain representation of the original input sequence.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] If the original sequence spans all the non-zero values of a function, its DTFT is continuous (and periodic), and the DFT provides discrete samples of one cycle.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] If the original sequence is one cycle of a periodic function, the DFT provides all the non-zero values of one DTFT cycle.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Reversing the time (i.e. replacing n by $N-n$ ) in $x_{n}$ corresponds to reversing the frequency (i.e. k by $N-k$ ).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] This table shows some mathematical operations on $x_{n}$ in the time domain and the corresponding effects on its DFT $X_{k}$ in the frequency domain.
