[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] These theorems are also equivalent to the unitary condition below.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Similarly, it can be shown that the IDFT formula leads to a periodic extension of $x_{n}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Multiplying $x_{n}$ by a *linear phase* $e^{{\frac {i2\pi }{N}}nm}$ for some integer *m* corresponds to a *circular shift* of the output $X_{k}$ : $X_{k}$ is replaced by $X_{k-m}$ , where the subscript is interpreted modulo *N* (i.e., periodically).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Similarly, a circular shift of the input $x_{n}$ corresponds to multiplying the output $X_{k}$ by a linear phase.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The convolution theorem for the discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT) indicates that a convolution of two sequences can be obtained as the inverse transform of the product of the individual transforms.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Customarily, the DFT and inverse DFT summations are taken over the domain $[0,N-1]$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] which gives rise to the interpretation as a *circular* convolution of x and $y.$ It is often used to efficiently compute their linear convolution.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] As seen above, the discrete Fourier transform has the fundamental property of carrying convolution into componentwise product.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] A natural question is whether it is the only one with this ability.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] It has been shown that any linear transform that turns convolution into pointwise product is the DFT up to a permutation of coefficients.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Since the number of permutations of n elements equals n!, there exist exactly n! linear and invertible maps with the same fundamental property as the DFT with respect to convolution.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where the coefficients *X**k* are given by the DFT of *x**n* above, satisfies the interpolation property $p(n/N)=x_{n}$ for $n=0,\ldots ,N-1$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] For even *N*, notice that the Nyquist component ${\textstyle {\frac {X_{N/2}}{N}}\cos(N\pi t)}$ is handled specially.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] This interpolation is *not unique*: aliasing implies that one could add *N* to any of the complex-sinusoid frequencies (e.g. changing $e^{-it}$ to $e^{i(N-1)t}$ ) without changing the interpolation property, but giving *different* values in between the $x_{n}$ points.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The choice above, however, is typical because it has two useful properties.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] First, it consists of sinusoids whose frequencies have the smallest possible magnitudes: the interpolation is bandlimited.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Second, if the $x_{n}$ are real numbers, then $p(t)$ is real as well.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In contrast, the most obvious trigonometric interpolation polynomial is the one in which the frequencies range from 0 to $N-1$ (instead of roughly $-N/2$ to $+N/2$ as above), similar to the inverse DFT formula.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] This interpolation does *not* minimize the slope, and is *not* generally real-valued for real $x_{n}$ ; its use is a common mistake.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where $\omega _{N}=e^{-i2\pi /N}$ is a primitive *N*th root of unity.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where $\det()$ is the determinant function.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The determinant is the product of the eigenvalues, which are always $\pm 1$ or $\pm i$ as described below.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In a real vector space, a unitary transformation can be thought of as simply a rigid rotation of the coordinate system, and all of the properties of a rigid rotation can be found in the unitary DFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] If we view the DFT as just a coordinate transformation which simply specifies the components of a vector in a new coordinate system, then the above is just the statement that the dot product of two vectors is preserved under a unitary DFT transformation.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] A consequence of the circular convolution theorem is that the DFT matrix F diagonalizes any circulant matrix.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] A useful property of the DFT is that the inverse DFT can be easily expressed in terms of the (forward) DFT, via several well-known "tricks".
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Third, a variant of this conjugation trick, which is sometimes preferable because it requires no modification of the data values, involves swapping real and imaginary parts (which can be done on a computer simply by modifying pointers).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Define ${\textstyle \operatorname {swap} (x_{n})}$ as $x_{n}$ with its real and imaginary parts swapped—that is, if $x_{n}=a+bi$ then ${\textstyle \operatorname {swap} (x_{n})}$ is $b+ai$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] That is, the inverse transform is the same as the forward transform with the real and imaginary parts swapped for both input and output, up to a normalization.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The conjugation trick can also be used to define a new transform, closely related to the DFT, that is involutory—that is, which is its own inverse.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] For real inputs $\mathbf {x}$ , the real part of $H(\mathbf {x} )$ is none other than the discrete Hartley transform, which is also involutory.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The eigenvalues of the DFT matrix are simple and well-known, whereas the eigenvectors are complicated, not unique, and are the subject of ongoing research.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Explicit formulas are given with a significant amount of number theory.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] This can be seen from the inverse properties above: operating $\mathbf {U}$ twice gives the original data in reverse order, so operating $\mathbf {U}$ four times gives back the original data and is thus the identity matrix.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Therefore, the eigenvalues of $\mathbf {U}$ are the fourth roots of unity: $\lambda$ is +1, −1, +*i*, or −*i*.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Since there are only four distinct eigenvalues for this $N\times N$ matrix, they have some multiplicity.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The multiplicity gives the number of linearly independent eigenvectors corresponding to each eigenvalue.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The problem of their multiplicity was solved by McClellan and Parks (1972), although it was later shown to have been equivalent to a problem solved by Gauss (Dickinson and Steiglitz, 1982).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] No simple analytical formula for general eigenvectors is known.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Moreover, the eigenvectors are not unique because any linear combination of eigenvectors for the same eigenvalue is also an eigenvector for that eigenvalue.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] hence, vector $\mathbf {u} (\lambda )$ is, indeed, the eigenvector of DFT matrix $\mathbf {U}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Operators ${\mathcal {P}}_{\lambda }$ project vectors onto subspaces which are orthogonal for each value of $\lambda$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] However, in general, projection operator method does not produce orthogonal eigenvectors within one subspace.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The operator ${\mathcal {P}}_{\lambda }$ can be seen as a matrix, whose columns are eigenvectors of $\mathbf {U}$ , but they are not orthogonal.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] However, the orthogonal set can be obtained by further applying orthogonalization algorithm to the set $\{\mathbf {u} _{n}(\lambda )\}_{n=1,\dots ,N_{\lambda }}$ , e.g.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] A straightforward approach to obtain DFT eigenvectors is to discretize an eigenfunction of the continuous Fourier transform, of which the most famous is the Gaussian function.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The choice of eigenvectors of the DFT matrix has become important in recent years in order to define a discrete analogue of the fractional Fourier transform—the DFT matrix can be taken to fractional powers by exponentiating the eigenvalues.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] For the continuous Fourier transform, the natural orthogonal eigenfunctions are the Hermite functions, so various discrete analogues of these have been employed as the eigenvectors of the DFT, such as the Kravchuk polynomials.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The "best" choice of eigenvectors to define a fractional discrete Fourier transform remains an open question, however.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Attempts were made to perform the fractional Fourier transform using confluent Vandermonde matrix.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where $D_{0}(X)$ and $D_{0}(x)$ are the variances of $|X|^{2}$ and $|x|^{2}$ respectively, with the equality attained in the case of a suitably normalized Gaussian distribution.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Although the variances may be analogously defined for the DFT, an analogous uncertainty principle is not useful, because the uncertainty will not be shift-invariant.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Still, a meaningful uncertainty principle has been introduced by Massar and Spindel.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] However, the Hirschman entropic uncertainty will have a useful analog for the case of the DFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The Hirschman uncertainty principle is expressed in terms of the Shannon entropy of the two probability functions.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The equality is obtained for $P_{n}$ equal to translations and modulations of a suitably normalized Kronecker comb of period A where A is any exact integer divisor of N .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The probability mass function $Q_{m}$ will then be proportional to a suitably translated Kronecker comb of period $B=N/A$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] There is also a well-known deterministic uncertainty principle that uses signal sparsity (or the number of non-zero coefficients).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] As an immediate consequence of the inequality of arithmetic and geometric means, one also has $2{\sqrt {N}}\leq \left\|x\right\|_{0}+\left\|X\right\|_{0}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Both uncertainty principles were shown to be tight for specifically chosen "picket-fence" sequences (discrete impulse trains), and find practical use for signal recovery applications.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] It follows that for even N $X_{0}$ and $X_{N/2}$ are real-valued, and the remainder of the DFT is completely specified by just $N/2-1$ complex numbers.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] It is possible to shift the transform sampling in time and/or frequency domain by some real shifts *a* and *b*, respectively.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Most often, shifts of $1/2$ (half a sample) are used.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] While the ordinary DFT corresponds to a periodic signal in both time and frequency domains, $a=1/2$ produces a signal that is anti-periodic in frequency domain ( $X_{k+N}=-X_{k}$ ) and vice versa for $b=1/2$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Thus, the specific case of $a=b=1/2$ is known as an *odd-time odd-frequency* discrete Fourier transform (or O2 DFT).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Such shifted transforms are most often used for symmetric data, to represent different boundary symmetries, and for real-symmetric data they correspond to different forms of the discrete cosine and sine transforms.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Another interesting choice is $a=b=-(N-1)/2$ , which is called the **centered DFT** (or **CDFT**).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The centered DFT has the useful property that, when *N* is a multiple of four, all four of its eigenvalues (see above) have equal multiplicities.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The term GDFT is also used for the non-linear phase extensions of DFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Hence, GDFT method provides a generalization for constant amplitude orthogonal block transforms including linear and non-linear phase types.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] GDFT is a framework to improve time and frequency domain properties of the traditional DFT, e.g. auto/cross-correlations, by the addition of the properly designed phase shaping function (non-linear, in general) to the original linear phase functions.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The discrete Fourier transform can be viewed as a special case of the z-transform, evaluated on the unit circle in the complex plane; more general z-transforms correspond to *complex* shifts *a* and *b* above.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The ordinary DFT transforms a one-dimensional sequence or array $x_{n}$ that is a function of exactly one discrete variable *n*.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where the division $\mathbf {n} /\mathbf {N}$ is defined as $\mathbf {n} /\mathbf {N} =(n_{1}/N_{1},\dots ,n_{d}/N_{d})$ to be performed element-wise, and the sum denotes the set of nested summations above.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] As the one-dimensional DFT expresses the input $x_{n}$ as a superposition of sinusoids, the multidimensional DFT expresses the input as a superposition of plane waves, or multidimensional sinusoids.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The direction of oscillation in space is $\mathbf {k} /\mathbf {N}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] This decomposition is of great importance for everything from digital image processing (two-dimensional) to solving partial differential equations.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The solution is broken up into plane waves.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The multidimensional DFT can be computed by the composition of a sequence of one-dimensional DFTs along each dimension.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In the two-dimensional case $x_{n_{1},n_{2}}$ the $N_{1}$ independent DFTs of the rows (i.e., along $n_{2}$ ) are computed first to form a new array $y_{n_{1},k_{2}}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Then the $N_{2}$ independent DFTs of *y* along the columns (along $n_{1}$ ) are computed to form the final result $X_{k_{1},k_{2}}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Alternatively the columns can be computed first and then the rows.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The order is immaterial because the nested summations above commute.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] An algorithm to compute a one-dimensional DFT is thus sufficient to efficiently compute a multidimensional DFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] This approach is known as the *row-column* algorithm.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] There are also intrinsically multidimensional FFT algorithms.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where the star again denotes complex conjugation and the $\ell$ -th subscript is again interpreted modulo $N_{\ell }$ (for $\ell =1,2,\ldots ,d$ ).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The DFT has seen wide usage across a large number of fields; we only sketch a few examples below (see also the references at the end).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] All applications of the DFT depend crucially on the availability of a fast algorithm to compute discrete Fourier transforms and their inverses, a fast Fourier transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] When the DFT is used for signal spectral analysis, the $\{x_{n}\}$ sequence usually represents a finite set of uniformly spaced time-samples of some signal $x(t)\,$ , where t represents time.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The conversion from continuous time to samples (discrete-time) changes the underlying Fourier transform of $x(t)$ into a discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT), which generally entails a type of distortion called aliasing.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Choice of an appropriate sample-rate (see *Nyquist rate*) is the key to minimizing that distortion.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Similarly, the conversion from a very long (or infinite) sequence to a manageable size entails a type of distortion called *leakage*, which is manifested as a loss of detail (a.k.a. resolution) in the DTFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Choice of an appropriate sub-sequence length is the primary key to minimizing that effect.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] When the available data (and time to process it) is more than the amount needed to attain the desired frequency resolution, a standard technique is to perform multiple DFTs, for example to create a spectrogram.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] A final source of distortion (or perhaps *illusion*) is the DFT itself, because it is just a discrete sampling of the DTFT, which is a function of a continuous frequency domain.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] That can be mitigated by increasing the resolution of the DFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] That procedure is illustrated at § Sampling the DTFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The discrete Fourier transform is widely used with spatial frequencies in modeling the way that light, electrons, and other probes travel through optical systems and scatter from objects in two and three dimensions.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] See § FFT filter banks and § Sampling the DTFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The field of digital signal processing relies heavily on operations in the frequency domain (i.e. on the Fourier transform).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] For example, several lossy image and sound compression methods employ the discrete Fourier transform: the signal is cut into short segments, each is transformed, and then the Fourier coefficients of high frequencies, which are assumed to be unnoticeable, are discarded.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The decompressor computes the inverse transform based on this reduced number of Fourier coefficients.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Some relatively recent compression algorithms, however, use wavelet transforms, which give a more uniform compromise between time and frequency domain than obtained by chopping data into segments and transforming each segment.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In the case of JPEG2000, this avoids the spurious image features that appear when images are highly compressed with the original JPEG.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Discrete Fourier transforms are often used to solve partial differential equations, where again the DFT is used as an approximation for the Fourier series (which is recovered in the limit of infinite *N*).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The advantage of this approach is that it expands the signal in complex exponentials $e^{inx}$ , which are eigenfunctions of differentiation: ${{\text{d}}{\big (}e^{inx}{\big )}}/{\text{d}}x=ine^{inx}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Thus, in the Fourier representation, differentiation is simple—we just multiply by $in$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] (However, the choice of n is not unique due to aliasing; for the method to be convergent, a choice similar to that in the trigonometric interpolation section above should be used.) A linear differential equation with constant coefficients is transformed into an easily solvable algebraic equation.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] One then uses the inverse DFT to transform the result back into the ordinary spatial representation.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Such an approach is called a spectral method.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Suppose we wish to compute the polynomial product *c*(*x*) = *a*(*x*) · *b*(*x*).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Here the vector product is taken elementwise.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] With a fast Fourier transform, the resulting algorithm takes *O*(*N* log *N*) arithmetic operations.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Due to its simplicity and speed, the Cooley–Tukey FFT algorithm, which is limited to composite sizes, is often chosen for the transform operation.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In this case, *d* should be chosen as the smallest integer greater than the sum of the input polynomial degrees that is factorizable into small prime factors (e.g.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] 2, 3, and 5, depending upon the FFT implementation).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The fastest known algorithms for the multiplication of very large integers use the polynomial multiplication method outlined above.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Integers can be treated as the value of a polynomial evaluated specifically at the number base, with the coefficients of the polynomial corresponding to the digits in that base (ex. $123=1\cdot 10^{2}+2\cdot 10^{1}+3\cdot 10^{0}$ ).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] After polynomial multiplication, a relatively low-complexity carry-propagation step completes the multiplication.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] When data is convolved with a function with wide support, such as for downsampling by a large sampling ratio, because of the Convolution theorem and the FFT algorithm, it may be faster to transform it, multiply pointwise by the transform of the filter and then reverse transform it.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Alternatively, a good filter is obtained by simply truncating the transformed data and re-transforming the shortened data set.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] The DFT can be interpreted as a complex-valued representation of the finite cyclic group.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] In other words, a sequence of n complex numbers can be thought of as an element of n -dimensional complex space $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ or equivalently a function f from the finite cyclic group of order n to the complex numbers, $\mathbb {Z} _{n}\mapsto \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] So f is a class function on the finite cyclic group, and thus can be expressed as a linear combination of the irreducible characters of this group, which are the roots of unity.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] From this point of view, one may generalize the DFT to representation theory generally, or more narrowly to the representation theory of finite groups.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] More narrowly still, one may generalize the DFT by either changing the target (taking values in a field other than the complex numbers), or the domain (a group other than a finite cyclic group), as detailed in the sequel.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] Many of the properties of the DFT only depend on the fact that $e^{-{\frac {i2\pi }{N}}}$ is a primitive root of unity, sometimes denoted $\omega _{N}$ or $W_{N}$ (so that $\omega _{N}^{N}=1$ ).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] Such properties include the completeness, orthogonality, Plancherel/Parseval, periodicity, shift, convolution, and unitarity properties above, as well as many FFT algorithms.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] For this reason, the discrete Fourier transform can be defined by using roots of unity in fields other than the complex numbers, and such generalizations are commonly called *number-theoretic transforms* (NTTs) in the case of finite fields.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] For more information, see number-theoretic transform and discrete Fourier transform (general).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] The standard DFT acts on a sequence *x*0, *x*1, ..., *x**N*−1 of complex numbers, which can be viewed as a function {0, 1, ..., *N* − 1} → **C**.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] This suggests the generalization to Fourier transforms on arbitrary finite groups, which act on functions *G* → **C** where *G* is a finite group.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] In this framework, the standard DFT is seen as the Fourier transform on a cyclic group, while the multidimensional DFT is a Fourier transform on a direct sum of cyclic groups.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] Further, Fourier transform can be on cosets of a group.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] There are various alternatives to the DFT for various applications, prominent among which are wavelets.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] The analog of the DFT is the discrete wavelet transform (DWT).
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] From the point of view of time–frequency analysis, a key limitation of the Fourier transform is that it does not include *location* information, only *frequency* information, and thus has difficulty in representing transients.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] As wavelets have location as well as frequency, they are better able to represent location, at the expense of greater difficulty representing frequency.
[src:fourier-analysis/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] For details, see comparison of the discrete wavelet transform with the discrete Fourier transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] A **fast Fourier transform** (**FFT**) is an algorithm that computes the discrete Fourier transform (DFT), or its inverse (IDFT), of a sequence.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] A Fourier transform converts a signal from its original domain (often time or space) to a representation in the frequency domain and vice versa.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The DFT is obtained by decomposing a sequence of values into components of different frequencies.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] This operation is useful in many fields, but computing it directly from the definition is often too slow to be practical.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] An FFT rapidly computes such transformations by factorizing the DFT matrix into a product of sparse (mostly zero) factors.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] As a result, it manages to reduce the complexity of computing the DFT from ${\textstyle O(n^{2})}$ , which arises if one simply applies the definition of DFT, to ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ , where n is the length of the sequence.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The difference in speed can be enormous, especially for long sequences where n may be in the thousands or millions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] As the FFT is merely an algebraic refactoring of terms within the DFT, the DFT and the FFT both perform mathematically equivalent and interchangeable operations, assuming that all terms are computed with infinite precision.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] However, in the presence of round-off error, many FFT algorithms are much more accurate than evaluating the DFT definition directly or indirectly.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] There are many different FFT algorithms based on a wide range of published theories, from simple complex-number arithmetic to group theory and number theory.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The best-known FFT algorithms depend upon the factorization of n, but there are FFTs with $O(n\log n)$ complexity for all n, including prime values.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Many FFT algorithms depend only on the fact that ${\textstyle e^{-2\pi i/n}}$ is an nth primitive root of unity, and thus can be applied to analogous transforms over any finite field, such as number-theoretic transforms.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Since the inverse DFT is the same as the DFT, but with the opposite sign in the exponent and a 1/*n* factor, any FFT algorithm can easily be adapted for it.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Fast Fourier transforms are widely used for applications in engineering, music, science, and mathematics.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The basic ideas were popularized in 1965, but some algorithms had been derived as early as 1805.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] In 1994, Gilbert Strang described the FFT as "the most important numerical algorithm of our lifetime", and it was included in Top 10 Algorithms of 20th Century by the IEEE magazine *Computing in Science & Engineering*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The development of fast algorithms for DFT was prefigured in Carl Friedrich Gauss's unpublished 1805 work on the orbits of asteroids Pallas and Juno.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Gauss wanted to interpolate the orbits from sample observations; his method was very similar to the one that would be published in 1965 by James Cooley and John Tukey, who are generally credited for the invention of the modern generic FFT algorithm.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] While Gauss's work predated even Joseph Fourier's 1822 results, he did not analyze the method's complexity, and eventually used other methods to achieve the same end.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Between 1805 and 1965, some versions of FFT were published by other authors.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Frank Yates in 1932 published his version called *interaction algorithm*, which provided efficient computation of Hadamard and Walsh transforms.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Yates' algorithm is still used in the field of statistical design and analysis of experiments.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Danielson and Cornelius Lanczos published their version to compute DFT for x-ray crystallography, a field where calculation of Fourier transforms presented a formidable bottleneck.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Good published a paper establishing the prime-factor FFT algorithm that applies to discrete Fourier transforms of size ${\textstyle n=n_{1}n_{2}}$ , where $n_{1}$ and $n_{2}$ are coprime.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] James Cooley and John Tukey independently rediscovered these earlier algorithms and published a more general FFT in 1965 that is applicable when n is composite and not necessarily a power of 2, as well as analyzing the ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ scaling.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Tukey came up with the idea during a meeting of President Kennedy's Science Advisory Committee, where a discussion topic involved detecting nuclear tests by the Soviet Union by setting up sensors to surround the country from outside.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] To analyze the output of these sensors, an FFT algorithm would be needed.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] In discussion with Tukey, Richard Garwin recognized the general applicability of the algorithm not just to national security problems, but also to a wide range of problems including one of immediate interest to him, determining the periodicities of the spin orientations in a 3-D crystal of Helium-3.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Garwin gave Tukey's idea to Cooley (both worked at IBM's Watson labs) for implementation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Cooley and Tukey published the paper in a relatively short time of six months.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] As Tukey did not work at IBM, the patentability of the idea was doubted and the algorithm went into the public domain, which, through the computing revolution of the next decade, made FFT one of the indispensable algorithms in digital signal processing.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] where $e^{i2\pi /n}$ is a primitive nth root of 1.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Evaluating this definition directly requires ${\textstyle O(n^{2})}$ operations: there are n outputs Xk , and each output requires a sum of n terms.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] An FFT is any method to compute the same results in ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ operations.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] All known FFT algorithms require ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ operations, although there is no known proof that lower complexity is impossible.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] To illustrate the savings of an FFT, consider the count of complex multiplications and additions for ${\textstyle n=4096}$ data points.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Evaluating the DFT's sums directly involves ${\textstyle n^{2}}$ complex multiplications and ${\textstyle n(n-1)}$ complex additions, of which ${\textstyle O(n)}$ operations can be saved by eliminating trivial operations such as multiplications by 1, leaving about 30 million operations.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] By far the most commonly used FFT is the Cooley–Tukey algorithm.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The best known use of the Cooley–Tukey algorithm is to divide the transform into two pieces of size *n*/2 at each step, and is therefore limited to power-of-two sizes, but any factorization can be used in general (as was known to both Gauss and Cooley/Tukey).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] These are called the *radix-2* and *mixed-radix* cases, respectively (and other variants such as the split-radix FFT have their own names as well).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Although the basic idea is recursive, most traditional implementations rearrange the algorithm to avoid explicit recursion.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Also, because the Cooley–Tukey algorithm breaks the DFT into smaller DFTs, it can be combined arbitrarily with any other algorithm for the DFT, such as those described below.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] For ${\textstyle n=n_{1}n_{2}}$ with coprime ${\textstyle n_{1}}$ and ${\textstyle n_{2}}$ , one can use the prime-factor (Good–Thomas) algorithm (PFA), based on the Chinese remainder theorem, to factorize the DFT similarly to Cooley–Tukey but without the twiddle factors.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Algorithms that recursively factorize the DFT into smaller operations other than DFTs include the Bruun and QFT algorithms.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] (The Rader–Brenner and QFT algorithms were proposed for power-of-two sizes, but it is possible that they could be adapted to general composite n.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Bruun's algorithm applies to arbitrary even composite sizes.) Bruun's algorithm, in particular, is based on interpreting the FFT as a recursive factorization of the polynomial $z^{n}-1$ , here into real-coefficient polynomials of the form $z^{m}-1$ and $z^{2m}+az^{m}+1$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] In particular, Winograd also makes use of the PFA as well as an algorithm by Rader for FFTs of *prime* sizes.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Hexagonal fast Fourier transform (HFFT) aims at computing an efficient FFT for the hexagonally-sampled data by using a new addressing scheme for hexagonal grids, called Array Set Addressing (ASA).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] and efficient FFT algorithms have been designed for this situation (see e.g., Sorensen, 1987).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] One approach consists of taking an ordinary algorithm (e.g., Cooley–Tukey) and removing the redundant parts of the computation, saving roughly a factor of two in time and memory.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Alternatively, it is possible to express an *even*-length real-input DFT as a complex DFT of half the length (whose real and imaginary parts are the even/odd elements of the original real data), followed by $O(n)$ post-processing operations.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Bruun's algorithm (above) is another method that was initially proposed to take advantage of real inputs, but it has not proved popular.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] There are further FFT specializations for the cases of real data that have even/odd symmetry, in which case one can gain another factor of roughly two in time and memory and the DFT becomes the discrete cosine/sine transform(s) (DCT/DST).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Instead of directly modifying an FFT algorithm for these cases, DCTs/DSTs can also be computed via FFTs of real data combined with $O(n)$ pre- and post-processing.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] What is the lower bound on the complexity of fast Fourier transform algorithms?
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] A fundamental question of longstanding theoretical interest is to prove lower bounds on the complexity and exact operation counts of fast Fourier transforms, and many open problems remain.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] It is not rigorously proved whether DFTs truly require ${\textstyle \Omega (n\log n)}$ (i.e., order *$n\log n$* or greater) operations, even for the simple case of power of two sizes, although no algorithms with lower complexity are known.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] In particular, the count of arithmetic operations is usually the focus of such questions, although actual performance on modern-day computers is determined by many other factors such as cache or CPU pipeline optimization.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Following work by Shmuel Winograd (1978), a tight $\Theta (n)$ lower bound is known for the number of real multiplications required by an FFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] It can be shown that only ${\textstyle 4n-2\log _{2}^{2}(n)-2\log _{2}(n)-4}$ irrational real multiplications are required to compute a DFT of power-of-two length $n=2^{m}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Moreover, explicit algorithms that achieve this count are known (Heideman & Burrus, 1986; Duhamel, 1990).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] However, these algorithms require too many additions to be practical, at least on modern computers with hardware multipliers (Duhamel, 1990; Frigo & Johnson, 2005).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] A tight lower bound is not known on the number of required additions, although lower bounds have been proved under some restrictive assumptions on the algorithms.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] In 1973, Morgenstern proved an $\Omega (n\log n)$ lower bound on the addition count for algorithms where the multiplicative constants have bounded magnitudes (which is true for most but not all FFT algorithms).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Pan (1986) proved an $\Omega (n\log n)$ lower bound assuming a bound on a measure of the FFT algorithm's *asynchronicity*, but the generality of this assumption is unclear.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] A third problem is to minimize the *total* number of real multiplications and additions, sometimes called the *arithmetic complexity* (although in this context it is the exact count and not the asymptotic complexity that is being considered).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Again, no tight lower bound has been proven.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Since 1968, however, the lowest published count for power-of-two n was long achieved by the split-radix FFT algorithm, which requires ${\textstyle 4n\log _{2}(n)-6n+8}$ real multiplications and additions for *n* > 1.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] This was further reduced to ${\textstyle \sim {\frac {34}{9}}n\log _{2}n}$ (Johnson and Frigo, 2007; Lundy and Van Buskirk, 2007).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Most of the attempts to lower or prove the complexity of FFT algorithms have focused on the ordinary complex-data case, because it is the simplest.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] However, complex-data FFTs are so closely related to algorithms for related problems, such as real-data FFTs, discrete cosine transforms, discrete Hartley transforms, and so on, that any improvement in one of these would immediately lead to improvements in the others (Duhamel & Vetterli, 1990).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] All of the FFT algorithms discussed above compute the DFT exactly (i.e., neglecting floating-point errors).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] A few FFT algorithms have been proposed, however, that compute the DFT *approximately*, with an error that can be made arbitrarily small at the expense of increased computations.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Such algorithms trade the approximation error for increased speed or other properties.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] For example, an approximate FFT algorithm by Edelman et al.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] (1999) achieves lower communication requirements for parallel computing with the help of a fast multipole method.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] A wavelet-based approximate FFT by Guo and Burrus (1996) takes sparse inputs/outputs (time/frequency localization) into account more efficiently than is possible with an exact FFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Another algorithm for approximate computation of a subset of the DFT outputs is due to Shentov et al.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The Edelman algorithm works equally well for sparse and non-sparse data, since it is based on the compressibility (rank deficiency) of the Fourier matrix itself rather than the compressibility (sparsity) of the data.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] FFT algorithms have errors when finite-precision floating-point arithmetic is used, but these errors are typically quite small; most FFT algorithms, e.g., Cooley–Tukey, have excellent numerical properties as a consequence of the pairwise summation structure of the algorithms.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The upper bound on the relative error for the Cooley–Tukey algorithm is ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon \log n)}$ , compared to ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon n^{3/2})}$ for the naïve DFT formula, where 𝜀 is the machine floating-point relative precision.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] In fact, the root mean square (rms) errors are much better than these upper bounds, being only ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon {\sqrt {\log n}})}$ for Cooley–Tukey and ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon {\sqrt {n}})}$ for the naïve DFT (Schatzman, 1996).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] These results, however, are very sensitive to the accuracy of the twiddle factors used in the FFT (i.e. the trigonometric function values), and it is not unusual for incautious FFT implementations to have much worse accuracy, e.g. if they use inaccurate trigonometric recurrence formulas.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Some FFTs other than Cooley–Tukey, such as the Rader–Brenner algorithm, are intrinsically less stable.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] In fixed-point arithmetic, the finite-precision errors accumulated by FFT algorithms are worse, with rms errors growing as ${\textstyle O({\sqrt {n}})}$ for the Cooley–Tukey algorithm (Welch, 1969).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Achieving this accuracy requires careful attention to scaling to minimize loss of precision, and fixed-point FFT algorithms involve rescaling at each intermediate stage of decompositions like Cooley–Tukey.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] To verify the correctness of an FFT implementation, rigorous guarantees can be obtained in ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ time by a simple procedure checking the linearity, impulse-response, and time-shift properties of the transform on random inputs (Ergün, 1995).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The values for intermediate frequencies may be obtained by various averaging methods.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Equivalently, it is the composition of a sequence of *d* sets of one-dimensional DFTs, performed along one dimension at a time (in any order).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] This compositional viewpoint immediately provides the simplest and most common multidimensional DFT algorithm, known as the **row-column** algorithm (after the two-dimensional case, below).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] That is, one simply performs a sequence of d one-dimensional FFTs (by any of the above algorithms): first you transform along the *n*1 dimension, then along the *n*2 dimension, and so on (actually, any ordering works).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] This method is easily shown to have the usual ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ complexity, where ${\textstyle n=n_{1}\cdot n_{2}\cdots n_{d}}$ is the total number of data points transformed.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] In more than two dimensions, it is often advantageous for cache locality to group the dimensions recursively.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] For example, a three-dimensional FFT might first perform two-dimensional FFTs of each planar slice for each fixed *n*1, and then perform the one-dimensional FFTs along the *n*1 direction.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Still, this remains a straightforward variation of the row-column algorithm that ultimately requires only a one-dimensional FFT algorithm as the base case, and still has $O(n\log n)$ complexity.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Yet another variation is to perform matrix transpositions in between transforming subsequent dimensions, so that the transforms operate on contiguous data; this is especially important for out-of-core and distributed memory situations where accessing non-contiguous data is extremely time-consuming.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] There are other multidimensional FFT algorithms that are distinct from the row-column algorithm, although all of them have ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ complexity.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Perhaps the simplest non-row-column FFT is the vector-radix FFT algorithm, which is a generalization of the ordinary Cooley–Tukey algorithm where one divides the transform dimensions by a vector ${\textstyle \mathbf {r} =\left(r_{1},r_{2},\ldots ,r_{d}\right)}$ of radices at each step.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] (This may also have cache benefits.) The simplest case of vector-radix is where all of the radices are equal (e.g., vector-radix-2 divides *all* of the dimensions by two), but this is not necessary.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Vector radix with only a single non-unit radix at a time, i.e. ${\textstyle \mathbf {r} =\left(1,\ldots ,1,r,1,\ldots ,1\right)}$ , is essentially a row-column algorithm.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Other, more complicated, methods include polynomial transform algorithms due to Nussbaumer (1977), which view the transform in terms of convolutions and polynomial products.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] See Duhamel and Vetterli (1990) for more information and references.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] A spherical-harmonic algorithm with ${\textstyle O(n^{2}\log n)}$ complexity is described by Rokhlin and Tygert.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The fast folding algorithm is analogous to the FFT, except that it operates on a series of binned waveforms rather than a series of real or complex scalar values.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Rotation (which in the FFT is multiplication by a complex phasor) is a circular shift of the component waveform .
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Various groups have also published FFT algorithms for non-equispaced data, as reviewed in Potts *et al.* (2001).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Such algorithms do not strictly compute the DFT (which is only defined for equispaced data), but rather some approximation thereof (a non-uniform discrete Fourier transform, or NDFT, which itself is often computed only approximately).
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] More generally, there are various other methods of spectral estimation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The FFT is used in digital recording, sampling, additive synthesis and pitch correction software.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The FFT's importance derives from the fact that it has made working in the frequency domain equally computationally feasible as working in the temporal or spatial domain.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] In modern wireless communication standards, the FFT is a critical component for processing signals.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Specifically, it is utilized in Orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing (OFDM) systems, such as 4G LTE and 5G NR.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The efficiency of the FFT allows for high-speed data transmission by dividing a wideband signal into multiple closely spaced orthogonal subcarriers.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] This technology is essential for reducing interference and optimizing power consumption in mobile devices.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] The FFT can be a poor choice for analyzing signals with non-stationary frequency content—where the frequency characteristics change over time.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] DFTs provide a global frequency estimate, assuming that all frequency components are present throughout the entire signal, which makes it challenging to detect short-lived or transient features within signals.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] For cases where frequency information appears briefly in the signal or generally varies over time, alternatives like the short-time Fourier transform, discrete wavelet transforms, or discrete Hilbert transform can be more suitable.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] These transforms allow for localized frequency analysis by capturing both frequency and time-based information.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] With the explosion of big data in fields such as astronomy, the need for 512K FFTs has arisen for certain interferometry calculations.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] require FFTs of tens of billions of points.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] As this size does not fit into main memory, so-called out-of-core FFTs are an active area of research.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] For applications such as MRI, it is necessary to compute DFTs for nonuniformly spaced grid points and/or frequencies.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Multipole-based approaches can compute approximate quantities with factor of runtime increase.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] A function on any compact group, including non-cyclic, has an expansion in terms of a basis of irreducible matrix elements.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] It remains an active area of research to find an efficient algorithm for performing this change of basis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] on a quantum computer has a subroutine to compute DFT of a binary vector.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] This is implemented as a sequence of 1- or 2-bit quantum gates now known as quantum FFT, which is effectively the Cooley–Tukey FFT realized as a particular factorization of the Fourier matrix.
[src:fourier-analysis/fast-fourier-transform] Extensions to these ideas are currently being explored.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Fourier analysis grew from the study of Fourier series, and is named after Joseph Fourier, who showed that representing a function as a sum of trigonometric functions greatly simplifies the study of heat transfer.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Fourier analysis has applications in many areas of pure and applied mathematics, in the sciences and in engineering.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The process of decomposing a function into oscillatory components is often called Fourier analysis, while the operation of rebuilding the function from these pieces is known as **Fourier synthesis**.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] For example, determining what component frequencies are present in a musical note would involve computing the Fourier transform of a sampled musical note.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] One can then re-synthesize the same sound by mixing purely harmonic sounds with frequency components as revealed in the Fourier analysis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] In mathematics, the term *Fourier analysis* often refers to the study of both operations.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The decomposition process itself is called a Fourier transformation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Its output, the Fourier transform, is often given a more specific name, which depends on the domain and other properties of the function being transformed.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Moreover, the original concept of Fourier analysis has been extended over time to apply to more and more abstract and general situations as group representation theory, and the general field is often known as harmonic analysis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Each transform used for analysis (see list of Fourier-related transforms) has a corresponding inverse transform that can be used for synthesis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] In applications, Fourier analysis is usually applied to a "signal" depending on "time" sampled at equal time intervals of length T .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The Fourier transform converts this sequence in an equally long sequence of amplitudes for sines and cosines (or more conveniently, complex exponentials) with frequency multiples of $1/T$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] This is particularly useful to detect strong periodic components in the signal.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The fast Fourier transform is an efficient algorithm to compute these amplitudes.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Different approaches have been developed for analyzing unequally spaced data, notably the least-squares spectral analysis (LSSA) methods that use a least squares fit of sinusoids to data samples, similar to Fourier analysis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Fourier analysis, the most used spectral method in science, generally boosts long-periodic noise in long gapped records; LSSA mitigates such problems.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] In forensics, laboratory infrared spectrophotometers use Fourier transform analysis for measuring the wavelengths of light at which a material will absorb in the infrared spectrum.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The FT method is used to decode the measured signals and record the wavelength data.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] And by using a computer, these Fourier calculations are rapidly carried out, so that in a matter of seconds, a computer-operated FT-IR instrument can produce an infrared absorption pattern comparable to that of a prism instrument.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Fourier transformation is also useful as a compact representation of a signal.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] For example, JPEG compression uses a variant of the Fourier transformation (discrete cosine transform) of small square pieces of a digital image.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The Fourier components of each square are rounded to lower arithmetic precision, and weak components are eliminated, so that the remaining components can be stored very compactly.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] In image reconstruction, each image square is reassembled from the preserved approximate Fourier-transformed components, which are then inverse-transformed to produce an approximation of the original image.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] In signal processing, the Fourier transform often takes a time series or a function of continuous time, and maps it into a frequency spectrum.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] When a function $s(t)$ is a function of time and represents a physical signal, the transform has a standard interpretation as the frequency spectrum of the signal.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The magnitude of the resulting complex-valued function $S(f)$ at frequency f represents the amplitude of a frequency component whose initial phase is given by the angle of $S(f)$ (polar coordinates).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Fourier transforms are not limited to functions of time, and temporal frequencies.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] They can equally be applied to analyze *spatial* frequencies, and indeed for nearly any function domain.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] This justifies their use in such diverse branches as image processing, heat conduction, and automatic control.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] When processing signals, such as audio, radio waves, light waves, seismic waves, and even images, Fourier analysis can isolate narrowband components of a compound waveform, concentrating them for easier detection or removal.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] A large family of signal processing techniques consist of Fourier-transforming a signal, manipulating the Fourier-transformed data in a simple way, and reversing the transformation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The fifth variant, the DFT, is used only in the case where the input function is discrete in its domain and limited to a finite region of support.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The DFT is the only variant that can be calculated numerically, and it can be used to approximate the other four variants.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Most often, the unqualified term **Fourier transform** refers to the transform of functions of a continuous real argument, and it produces a continuous function of frequency, known as a *frequency distribution* or *spectrum*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] One function is transformed into another, and the operation is reversible.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Evaluating this quantity for all values of f produces the *frequency-domain* function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Note that any $s(t)$ whose transform has the same discrete sample values can be used in the periodic summation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] A sufficient condition for recovering $s(t)$ (and therefore $S(f)$ ) from just these samples (i.e. from the Fourier series) is that the non-zero portion of $s(t)$ be confined to a known interval of duration $P,$ which is the frequency domain dual of the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] See Fourier series for more information, including the historical development.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The DTFT is the mathematical dual of the time-domain Fourier series.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Thus the **DTFT** of the $s[n]$ sequence is also the **Fourier transform** of the modulated Dirac comb function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Parameter T corresponds to the sampling interval, and this Fourier series can now be recognized as a form of the Poisson summation formula.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] But under certain idealized conditions one can theoretically recover $S(f)$ and $s(t)$ exactly.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] This is a cornerstone in the foundation of digital signal processing.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Another reason to be interested in $S_{\tfrac {1}{T}}(f)$ is that it often provides insight into the amount of aliasing caused by the sampling process.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Applications of the DTFT are not limited to sampled functions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The $S[k]$ sequence is customarily known as the **DFT** of one cycle of $s_{_{N}}.$ It is also N -periodic, so it is never necessary to compute more than N coefficients.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Conversely, when one wants to compute an arbitrary number $(N)$ of discrete samples of one cycle of a continuous DTFT, $S_{\tfrac {1}{T}}(f),$ it can be done by computing the relatively simple DFT of $s_{_{N}}[n],$ as defined above.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] (see Discrete-time Fourier transform § L=N×I) In most cases of practical interest, the $s[n]$ sequence represents a longer sequence that was truncated by the application of a finite-length window function or FIR filter array.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The DFT can be computed using a fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithm, which makes it a practical and important transformation on computers.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] For periodic functions, both the Fourier transform and the DTFT comprise only a discrete set of frequency components (Fourier series), and the transforms diverge at those frequencies.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] One common practice (not discussed above) is to handle that divergence via Dirac delta and Dirac comb functions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] But the same spectral information can be discerned from just one cycle of the periodic function, since all the other cycles are identical.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Similarly, finite-duration functions can be represented as a Fourier series, with no actual loss of information except that the periodicity of the inverse transform is a mere artifact.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] It is common in practice for the duration of *s*(•) to be limited to the period, P or N.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] But these formulas do not require that condition.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] When the real and imaginary parts of a complex function are decomposed into their even and odd parts, there are four components, denoted below by the subscripts RE, RO, IE, and IO.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] An early form of harmonic series dates back to ancient Babylonian mathematics, where they were used to compute ephemerides (tables of astronomical positions).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The Classical Greek concepts of deferent and epicycle in the Ptolemaic system of astronomy were related to Fourier series (see Deferent and epicycle § Mathematical formalism).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] In modern times, variants of the discrete Fourier transform were used by Alexis Clairaut in 1754 to compute an orbit, which has been described as the first formula for the DFT, and in 1759 by Joseph Louis Lagrange, in computing the coefficients of a trigonometric series for a vibrating string.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Technically, Clairaut's work was a cosine-only series (a form of discrete cosine transform), while Lagrange's work was a sine-only series (a form of discrete sine transform); a true cosine+sine DFT was used by Gauss in 1805 for trigonometric interpolation of asteroid orbits.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Euler and Lagrange both discretized the vibrating string problem, using what would today be called samples.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] where ζ is a cubic root of unity, which is the DFT of order 3.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] Independently of Fourier, astronomer Friedrich Wilhelm Bessel also introduced Fourier series to solve Kepler's equation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] His work was published in 1819, unaware of Fourier's work which remained unpublished until 1822.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The subsequent development of the field is known as harmonic analysis, and is also an early instance of representation theory.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The first fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithm for the DFT was discovered around 1805 by Carl Friedrich Gauss when interpolating measurements of the orbit of the asteroids Juno and Pallas, although that particular FFT algorithm is more often attributed to its modern rediscoverers Cooley and Tukey.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] In signal processing terms, a function (of time) is a representation of a signal with perfect *time resolution*, but no frequency information, while the Fourier transform has perfect *frequency resolution*, but no time information.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] As alternatives to the Fourier transform, in time–frequency analysis, one uses time–frequency transforms to represent signals in a form that has some time information and some frequency information – by the uncertainty principle, there is a trade-off between these.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] The Fourier variants can also be generalized to Fourier transforms on arbitrary locally compact Abelian topological groups, which are studied in harmonic analysis; there, the Fourier transform takes functions on a group to functions on the dual group.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] This treatment also allows a general formulation of the convolution theorem, which relates Fourier transforms and convolutions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] See also the Pontryagin duality for the generalized underpinnings of the Fourier transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-analysis] More specific, Fourier analysis can be done on cosets, even discrete cosets.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] A **Fourier series** (/ˈfʊrieɪ, -iər/) is a series expansion of a periodic function into a sum of trigonometric functions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series is an example of a trigonometric series.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] By expressing a function as a sum of sines and cosines, many problems involving the function become easier to analyze because trigonometric functions are well understood.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] For example, Fourier series were first used by Joseph Fourier to find solutions to the heat equation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This application is possible because the derivatives of trigonometric functions fall into simple patterns.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Fourier series cannot be used to approximate arbitrary functions, because most functions have infinitely many terms in their Fourier series, and the series do not always converge.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Well-behaved functions, for example smooth functions, have Fourier series that converge to the original function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The coefficients of the Fourier series are determined by integrals of the function multiplied by trigonometric functions, described in Fourier series § Definition.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The study of the convergence of Fourier series focus on the behaviors of the *partial sums*, which means studying the behavior of the sum as more and more terms from the series are summed.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The figures below illustrate some partial Fourier series results for the components of a square wave.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Fourier series are closely related to the Fourier transform, a more general tool that can even find the frequency information for functions that are *not* periodic.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Periodic functions can be identified with functions on a circle; for this reason Fourier series are the subject of Fourier analysis on the circle group, denoted by $\mathbb {T}$ or $S_{1}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier transform is also part of Fourier analysis, but is defined for functions on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Since Fourier's time, many different approaches to defining and understanding the concept of Fourier series have been discovered, all of which are consistent with one another, but each of which emphasizes different aspects of the topic.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Some of the more powerful and elegant approaches are based on mathematical ideas and tools that were not available in Fourier's time.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Fourier originally defined the Fourier series for real-valued functions of real arguments, and used the sine and cosine functions in the series expansion.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Many other Fourier-related transforms have since been defined, extending his initial idea to many applications and birthing an area of mathematics called Fourier analysis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series is named in honor of Jean-Baptiste Joseph Fourier (1768–1830), who made important contributions to the study of trigonometric series, after preliminary investigations by Leonhard Euler, Jean le Rond d'Alembert, and Daniel Bernoulli.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The *Mémoire* introduced Fourier analysis, specifically Fourier series.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Through Fourier's research the fact was established that an arbitrary (at first, continuous and later generalized to any piecewise-smooth) function can be represented by a trigonometric series.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The first announcement of this great discovery was made by Fourier in 1807, before the French Academy.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Early ideas of decomposing a periodic function into the sum of simple oscillating functions date back to the 3rd century BC, when ancient astronomers proposed an empiric model of planetary motions, based on deferents and epicycles.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Independently of Fourier, astronomer Friedrich Wilhelm Bessel introduced Fourier series to solve Kepler's equation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The heat equation is a partial differential equation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Prior to Fourier's work, no solution to the heat equation was known in the general case, although particular solutions were known if the heat source behaved in a simple way, in particular, if the heat source was a sine or cosine wave.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] These simple solutions are now sometimes called eigensolutions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Fourier's idea was to model a complicated heat source as a superposition (or linear combination) of simple sine and cosine waves, and to write the solution as a superposition of the corresponding eigensolutions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This superposition or linear combination is called the Fourier series.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] From a modern point of view, Fourier's results are somewhat informal, due to the lack of a precise notion of function and integral in the early nineteenth century.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Later, Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet and Bernhard Riemann expressed Fourier's results with greater precision and formality.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series has many such applications in electrical engineering, vibration analysis, acoustics, optics, signal processing, image processing, quantum mechanics, econometrics, shell theory, etc.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] — Joseph Fourier, Mémoire sur la propagation de la chaleur dans les corps solides (1807).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This immediately gives any coefficient *ak* of the trigonometric series for φ(*y*) for any function which has such an expansion.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] In these few lines, which are close to the modern formalism used in Fourier series, Fourier revolutionized both mathematics and physics.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Although similar trigonometric series were previously used by Euler, d'Alembert, Daniel Bernoulli and Gauss, Fourier believed that such trigonometric series could represent any arbitrary function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] In what sense that is actually true is a somewhat subtle issue and the attempts over many years to clarify this idea have led to important discoveries in the theories of convergence, function spaces, and harmonic analysis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series expansion of the sawtooth function (below) looks more complicated than the simple formula $s(x)={\tfrac {x}{\pi }}$ , so it is not immediately apparent why one would need the Fourier series.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] While there are many applications, Fourier's motivation was in solving the heat equation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] For example, consider a metal plate in the shape of a square whose sides measure $\pi$ meters, with coordinates $(x,y)\in [0,\pi ]\times [0,\pi ]$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Here, $\sinh$ is the hyperbolic sine function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This solution of the heat equation is obtained by multiplying each term of the equation from Analysis § Example by $\sinh(ny)/\sinh(n\pi )$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] While our example function $s(x)$ seems to have a needlessly complicated Fourier series, the heat distribution $T(x,y)$ is nontrivial.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The function T cannot be written as a closed-form expression.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This method of solving the heat problem was made possible by Fourier's work.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Another application is to solve the Basel problem by using Parseval's theorem.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The example generalizes and one may compute ζ(2*n*), for any positive integer *n*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] However, these are not necessary conditions and there are many theorems about different types of convergence of Fourier series (e.g. uniform convergence or mean convergence).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The definition naturally extends to the Fourier series of a (periodic) distribution s (also called *Fourier-Schwartz series*).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Then the Fourier series converges to $s(x)$ in the distribution sense.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The process of determining the Fourier coefficients of a given function or signal is called ***analysis***, while forming the associated trigonometric series (or its various approximations) is called ***synthesis***.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The harmonics are indexed by an integer, $n,$ which is also the number of cycles the corresponding sinusoids make in interval P .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] These series can represent functions that are just a sum of one or more frequencies in the harmonic spectrum.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] In the limit $N\to \infty$ , a trigonometric series can also represent the intermediate frequencies or non-sinusoidal functions because of the infinite number of terms.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The coefficients can be given/assumed, such as a music synthesizer or time samples of a waveform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] In the latter case, the exponential form of Fourier series synthesizes a discrete-time Fourier transform where variable x represents frequency instead of time.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] In general, the coefficients are determined by *analysis* of a given function $s(x)$ whose domain of definition is an interval of length P .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The ${\tfrac {2}{P}}$ scale factor follows from substituting **Eq.1** into **Eq.3** and utilizing the orthogonality of the trigonometric system.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] with $c_{0}$ being the mean value of s on the interval P .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This is a particular instance of the Dirichlet theorem for Fourier series.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This example leads to a solution of the Basel problem.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] where $A_{n}$ is the amplitude and $\varphi _{n}$ is the phase shift of the $n^{th}$ harmonic.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] An example of determining the parameter $\varphi _{n}$ for one value of n is shown in Figure 2.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] It is the value of $\varphi$ at the maximum correlation between $s(x)$ and a cosine *template,* $\cos(2\pi {\tfrac {n}{P}}x-\varphi )$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The notation $c_{n}$ is inadequate for discussing the Fourier coefficients of several different functions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] In engineering, particularly when the variable x represents time, the coefficient sequence is called a frequency domain representation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Square brackets are often used to emphasize that the domain of this function is a discrete set of frequencies.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] where f represents a continuous frequency domain.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] When variable x has units of seconds, f has units of hertz.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The constructed function $S(f)$ is therefore commonly referred to as a **Fourier transform**, even though the Fourier integral of a periodic function is not convergent at the harmonic frequencies.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Some common pairs of periodic functions and their Fourier series coefficients are shown in the table below.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This table shows some mathematical operations in the time domain and the corresponding effect in the Fourier series coefficients.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] If s is a P -periodic function on $\mathbb {R}$ which is k times differentiable, and its $k^{\text{th}}$ derivative is continuous, then s belongs to the function space $C^{k}(\mathbb {R} )$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] One of the interesting properties of the Fourier transform which we have mentioned, is that it carries convolutions to pointwise products.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] If that is the property which we seek to preserve, one can produce Fourier series on any compact group.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Typical examples include those classical groups that are compact.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This generalizes the Fourier transform to all spaces of the form *L*2(*G*), where *G* is a compact group, in such a way that the Fourier transform carries convolutions to pointwise products.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series exists and converges in similar ways to the [−*π*,*π*] case.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] An alternative extension to compact groups is the Peter–Weyl theorem, which proves results about representations of compact groups analogous to those about finite groups.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] If the domain is not a group, then there is no intrinsically defined convolution.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] However, if X is a compact Riemannian manifold, it has a Laplace–Beltrami operator.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The Laplace–Beltrami operator is the differential operator that corresponds to Laplace operator for the Riemannian manifold X .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Then, by analogy, one can consider heat equations on X .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Since Fourier arrived at his basis by attempting to solve the heat equation, the natural generalization is to use the eigensolutions of the Laplace–Beltrami operator as a basis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This generalizes Fourier series to spaces of the type $L^{2}(X)$ , where X is a Riemannian manifold.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series converges in ways similar to the $[-\pi ,\pi ]$ case.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] A typical example is to take X to be the sphere with the usual metric, in which case the Fourier basis consists of spherical harmonics.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The generalization to compact groups discussed above does not generalize to noncompact, nonabelian groups.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] However, there is a straightforward generalization to Locally Compact Abelian (LCA) groups.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This generalizes the Fourier transform to $L^{1}(G)$ or $L^{2}(G)$ , where G is an LCA group.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] If G is compact, one also obtains a Fourier series, which converges similarly to the $[-\pi ,\pi ]$ case, but if G is noncompact, one obtains instead a Fourier integral.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This generalization yields the usual Fourier transform when the underlying locally compact Abelian group is $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] As such, when $\mu \in M$ , the function ${\hat {\mu }}(n)$ is also referred to as a Fourier-Stieltjes transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This follows from an earlier and more concrete representation of a Radon measure (i.e. a locally finite Borel measure) on $\mathbb {R}$ , given by F.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] As the distributional derivative of F is a Radon measure, it is subject to the Lebesgue decomposition and can be expressed as $dF=F'dx+dF_{s}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] If $dF_{s}=0$ the expression reduces to the original definition of the Fourier coefficients, hence a Fourier series is a Fourier-Stieltjes series.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The question whether or not $\mu$ exists for a given sequence of $c_{n}$ forms the basis of the trigonometric moment problem.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series can be generalized still further from measures to distributions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] If the Fourier coefficients are determined by a distribution $F\in {\mathcal {D}}'$ then the series is sometimes described as a *Fourier-Schwartz series*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] While it is often extremely difficult to decide whether a given series is a Fourier or a Fourier-Stieltjes series, deciding whether or not it is a Fourier-Schwartz series is relatively trivial.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Aside from being useful for solving partial differential equations such as the heat equation, one notable application of Fourier series on the square is in image compression.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] In particular, the JPEG image compression standard uses the two-dimensional discrete cosine transform, a discrete form of the Fourier cosine transform, which uses only cosine as the basis function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] For two-dimensional arrays with a staggered appearance, half of the Fourier series coefficients disappear, due to additional symmetry.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] A three-dimensional Bravais lattice is defined as the set of vectors of the form $\mathbf {R} =n_{1}\mathbf {a} _{1}+n_{2}\mathbf {a} _{2}+n_{3}\mathbf {a} _{3}$ where $n_{i}$ are integers and $\mathbf {a} _{i}$ are three linearly independent but not necessarily orthogonal vectors.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Let us consider some function $f(\mathbf {r} )$ with the same periodicity as the Bravais lattice, *i.e.* $f(\mathbf {r} )=f(\mathbf {R} +\mathbf {r} )$ for any lattice vector $\mathbf {R}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This situation frequently occurs in solid-state physics where $f(\mathbf {r} )$ might, for example, represent the effective potential that an electron "feels" inside a periodic crystal.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] In presence of such a periodic potential, the quantum-mechanical description of the electron results in a periodically modulated plane-wave commonly known as Bloch state.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] As the trigonometric series is a special class of orthogonal system, Fourier series can naturally be defined in the context of Hilbert spaces.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] For example, the space of square-integrable functions on $[-\pi ,\pi ]$ forms the Hilbert space $L^{2}([-\pi ,\pi ])$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Its inner product, defined for any two elements f and g , is given by: $\langle f,g\rangle ={\frac {1}{2\pi }}\int _{-\pi }^{\pi }f(x){\overline {g(x)}}\,dx.$ This space is equipped with the orthonormal basis $\left\{e_{n}=e^{inx}:n\in \mathbb {Z} \right\}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The sine-cosine form follows in a similar fashion.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The density of their span is a consequence of the Stone–Weierstrass theorem, but follows also from the properties of classical kernels like the Fejér kernel.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] In engineering, the Fourier series is generally assumed to converge except at jump discontinuities since the functions encountered in engineering are usually better-behaved than those in other disciplines.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] In particular, if s is continuous and the derivative of $s(x)$ (which may not exist everywhere) is square integrable, then the Fourier series of s converges absolutely and uniformly to $s(x)$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] If a function is square-integrable on the interval $[x_{0},x_{0}+P]$ , then the Fourier series converges to the function almost everywhere.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] It is possible to define Fourier coefficients for more general functions or distributions, in which case pointwise convergence often fails, and convergence in norm or weak convergence is usually studied.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Because of the least squares property, and because of the completeness of the Fourier basis, we obtain an elementary convergence result.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] If s is continuously differentiable, then $(in)S[n]$ is the n th Fourier coefficient of the first derivative $s'$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Since $s'$ is continuous, and therefore bounded, it is square-integrable and its Fourier coefficients are square-summable.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This means that s is absolutely summable.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] This result can be proven easily if s is further assumed to be $\textstyle C^{2}$ , since in that case $\textstyle n^{2}S[n]$ tends to zero as $n\rightarrow \infty$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] More generally, the Fourier series is absolutely summable, thus converges uniformly to s , provided that s satisfies a Hölder condition of order $\alpha >{\tfrac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Since Fourier series have such good convergence properties, many are often surprised by some of the negative results.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] For example, the Fourier series of a continuous *T*-periodic function need not converge pointwise.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] The uniform boundedness principle yields a simple non-constructive proof of this fact.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] In 1922, Andrey Kolmogorov published an article titled *Une série de Fourier-Lebesgue divergente presque partout* in which he gave an example of a Lebesgue-integrable function whose Fourier series diverges almost everywhere.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] He later constructed an example of an integrable function whose Fourier series diverges everywhere.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] As m increases, the coefficients will be positive and increasing until they reach a value of about $C_{m}\approx 2/(n^{2}\pi )$ at $m=2^{n^{3}}/2$ for some n and then become negative (starting with a value around $-2/(n^{2}\pi )$ ) and getting smaller, before starting a new such wave.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] in the nth wave before returning to around zero, showing that the series does not converge at zero but reaches higher and higher peaks.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-series] Note that though the function is continuous, it is not differentiable.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In mathematics, the **Fourier transform** (**FT**) is an integral transform that takes a function as input and outputs another function that describes the extent to which various frequencies are present in the original function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The output of the transform is a complex valued function of frequency.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The term *Fourier transform* refers to both the mathematical operation and to this complex-valued function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When a distinction needs to be made, the output of the operation is sometimes called the frequency domain representation of the original function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform is analogous to decomposing the sound of a musical chord into the intensities of its constituent pitches.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Functions that are localized in the time domain have Fourier transforms that are spread out across the frequency domain and vice versa, a phenomenon known as the uncertainty principle.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The critical case for this principle is the Gaussian function, of substantial importance in probability theory and statistics as well as in the study of physical phenomena exhibiting normal distribution (e.g., diffusion).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform of a Gaussian function is another Gaussian function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Joseph Fourier introduced sine and cosine transforms (which correspond to the imaginary and real components of the modern Fourier transform) in his study of heat transfer, where Gaussian functions appear as solutions of the heat equation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform can be formally defined as an improper Riemann integral, making it an integral transform, although this definition is not suitable for many applications requiring a more sophisticated integration theory.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] For example, many relatively simple applications use the Dirac delta function, which can be treated formally as if it were a function, but the justification requires a mathematically more sophisticated viewpoint.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform can also be generalized to functions of several variables on Euclidean space, sending a function of 3-dimensional "position space" to a function of 3-dimensional momentum (or a function of space and time to a function of 4-momentum).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This idea makes the spatial Fourier transform very natural in the study of waves, as well as in quantum mechanics, where it is important to be able to represent wave solutions as functions of either position or momentum and sometimes both.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In general, functions to which Fourier methods are applicable are complex-valued, and possibly vector-valued.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The latter is routinely employed to handle periodic functions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The fast Fourier transform (FFT) is an algorithm for computing the DFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When $f(x)$ is (Lebesgue) integrable over the whole real line, the above integral converges for all $\xi \in \mathbb {R}$ , and ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )$ is a uniformly continuous function of $\xi$ which decays to zero as ⁠ $\xi \to \infty$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] However, the Fourier transform can also be defined for (generalized) functions for which the Lebesgue integral **Eq.1** does not make sense.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Interpreting the integral suitably (e.g. as an improper integral for locally integrable functions) extends the Fourier transform to functions that are not necessarily integrable over the whole real line.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] More generally, the Fourier transform also applies to generalized functions like the Dirac delta (and all other tempered distributions), in which case it is defined by duality rather than an integral.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The functions f and ${\widehat {f}}$ are referred to as a **Fourier transform pair**.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When the independent variable (⁠ x ⁠) represents *time* (often denoted by ⁠ t ⁠), the transform variable (⁠ $\xi$ ⁠) represents frequency (often denoted by ⁠ f ⁠).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] For example, if time has the unit second, then frequency has the unit hertz.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The transform variable can also be written in terms of angular frequency, ⁠ $\omega =2\pi \xi$ ⁠, with the unit radian per second.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Furthermore, ${\widehat {f}}\in L^{\infty }\cap C_{0}(\mathbb {R} )$ is bounded, uniformly continuous and (by the Riemann–Lebesgue lemma) vanishing at infinity.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Here $C_{0}(\mathbb {R} )$ denotes the space of continuous functions on $\mathbb {R}$ that approach 0 as x approaches positive or negative infinity.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The space $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ is the space of measurable functions for which the norm $\|f\|_{1}$ is finite, modulo the equivalence relation of equality almost everywhere.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform on $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ is one-to-one.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] However, there is no easy characterization of the image, and thus no easy characterization of the inverse transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In particular, **Eq.2** is no longer valid, as it was stated only under the hypothesis that $f(x)$ was "sufficiently nice" (e.g., $f(x)$ decays with all derivatives).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] While **Eq.1** defines the Fourier transform for (complex-valued) functions in ⁠ $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠, it is not well-defined for other integrability classes, most importantly the space of square-integrable functions ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] However, the Fourier transform on the dense subspace $L^{1}\cap L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )\subset L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ admits a unique continuous extension to a unitary operator on ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This extension is important in part because, unlike the case of ⁠ $L^{1}$ ⁠, the Fourier transform is an automorphism of the space ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In such cases, the Fourier transform can be obtained explicitly by regularizing the integral, and then passing to a limit.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In practice, the integral is often regarded as an improper integral instead of a proper Lebesgue integral, but sometimes for convergence one needs to use weak limit or principal value instead of the (pointwise) limits implicit in an improper integral.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Titchmarsh (1986) and Dym & McKean (1985) each gives three rigorous ways of extending the Fourier transform to square integrable functions using this procedure.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] A general principle in working with the $L^{2}$ Fourier transform is that finite linear combinations of Gaussians are dense in ⁠ $L^{1}\cap L^{2}$ ⁠, and the various features of the Fourier transform, such as its unitarity, are easily inferred for Gaussians.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] A feature of the $L^{1}$ Fourier transform is that it is a homomorphism of Banach algebras from $L^{1}$ equipped with the convolution operation to the Banach algebra of continuous functions under the $L^{\infty }$ (supremum) norm.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The conventions chosen in this article are those of harmonic analysis, such that the Fourier transform is both unitary on ⁠ $L^{2}$ ⁠ and an algebra homomorphism from ⁠ ${1}$ ⁠ to ⁠ $L^{\infty }$ ⁠, without renormalizing the Lebesgue measure.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In 1822, Fourier claimed (see *Joseph Fourier § The Analytic Theory of Heat*) that any function, whether continuous or discontinuous, can be expanded into a series of sines.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] That important work was corrected and expanded upon by others to provide the foundation for the various forms of the Fourier transform used since.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Likewise, the intuitive interpretation of **Eq.1** is that multiplying $f(x)$ by $e^{-i2\pi \xi x}$ has the effect of subtracting $\xi$ from every frequency component of function ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Only the component that was at frequency $\xi$ can produce a non-zero value of the infinite integral, because (at least formally) all the other shifted components are oscillatory and integrate to zero (see *§ Example*).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] It is noteworthy how easily the product was simplified using the polar form, and how easily the rectangular form was deduced by an application of Euler's formula.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Euler's formula introduces the possibility of negative ⁠ $\xi$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Only certain complex-valued $f(x)$ have transforms ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}=0,\ \forall \ \xi <0$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] (See *Analytic signal*; a simple example is ⁠ $e^{i2\pi \xi _{0}x}\ (\xi _{0}>0)$ ⁠.) But negative frequency is necessary to characterize all other complex-valued ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠, found in signal processing, partial differential equations, radar, nonlinear optics, quantum mechanics, and others.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] But it cannot determine the actual sign of ⁠ $\xi _{0}$ ⁠, because $\cos(2\pi \xi _{0}x)$ and $\cos(2\pi (-\xi _{0})x)$ are indistinguishable on just the real numbers line.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform of a periodic function cannot be defined using the integral formula directly.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In order for integral in **Eq.1** to be defined the function must be absolutely integrable.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Instead it is common to use Fourier series.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] It is possible to extend the definition to include periodic functions by viewing them as tempered distributions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This makes it possible to see a connection between the Fourier series and the Fourier transform for periodic functions that have a convergent Fourier series.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In other words, the Fourier transform is a Dirac comb function whose *teeth* are multiplied by the Fourier series coefficients.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform of an integrable function f can be sampled at regular intervals of arbitrary length ⁠ $1/P$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The integrability of f ensures the periodic summation converges.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When $f(x)$ has compact support, $f_{P}(x)$ has a finite number of terms within the interval of integration.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When $f(x)$ does not have compact support, numerical evaluation of $f_{P}(x)$ requires an approximation, such as tapering $f(x)$ or truncating the number of terms.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The frequency variable must have inverse units to the units of the original function's domain (typically named t or ⁠ x ⁠).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] For example, if t is measured in seconds, $\xi$ should be in cycles per second or hertz.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] If the scale of time is in units of $2\pi$ seconds, then another Greek letter $\omega$ is typically used instead to represent angular frequency (where ⁠ $\omega =2\pi \xi$ ⁠) in units of radians per second.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] If using x for units of length, then $\xi$ must be in inverse length, e.g., wavenumbers.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] That is to say, there are two versions of the real line: one that is the range of t and measured in units of ⁠ t ⁠, and the other that is the range of $\xi$ and measured in inverse units to the units of ⁠ t ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] These two distinct versions of the real line cannot be equated with each other.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Therefore, the Fourier transform goes from one space of functions to a different space of functions: functions that have a different domain of definition.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In general, $\xi$ must always be taken to be a linear form on the space of its domain, which is to say that the second real line is the dual space of the first real line.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] (See the article *Linear algebra* for a more formal explanation and for more details.) This point of view becomes essential in generalizations of the Fourier transform to general symmetry groups, including the case of Fourier series.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The various definitions resulting from different choices of units differ by various constants.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In other conventions, the Fourier transform has i in the exponent instead of −*i*, and vice versa for the inversion formula.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This convention is common in modern physics and is the default for Wolfram Alpha, and does not mean that the frequency has become negative, since there is no canonical definition of positivity for frequency of a complex wave.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Many of the identities involving the Fourier transform remain valid in those conventions, provided all terms that explicitly involve *i* have it replaced by −*i*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In electrical engineering the letter *j* is typically used for the imaginary unit instead of *i* because *i* is used for current.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When using dimensionless units, the constant factors might not be written in the transform definition.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In probability theory and mathematical statistics, the use of the Fourier—Stieltjes transform is preferred, because many random variables are not of continuous type, and do not possess a density function, and one must treat not functions but distributions, i.e., measures that possess "atoms".
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] From the higher point of view of group characters, which is much more abstract, all these arbitrary choices disappear, as will be explained in the later section of this article, which treats the notion of the Fourier transform of a function on a locally compact abelian group.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Let $f(x)$ and $h(x)$ represent *integrable functions* Lebesgue-measurable on the real line satisfying: $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }|f(x)|\,dx<\infty .$ We denote the Fourier transforms of these functions as ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )$ and ${\widehat {h}}(\xi )$ respectively.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In particular, if f is *real*, then ${\widehat {f}}$ is conjugate symmetric (a.k.a.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The integral of f over its domain is the total mass or DC bias of the function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform may be defined in some cases for non-integrable functions, but the Fourier transforms of integrable functions have several strong properties.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] However, ${\widehat {f}}$ need not be integrable.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] For example, the Fourier transform of the rectangular function, which is integrable, is the sinc function, which is not Lebesgue integrable, because its improper integrals behave analogously to the alternating harmonic series, in converging to a sum without being absolutely convergent.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] It is not generally possible to write the *inverse transform* as a Lebesgue integral.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] However, when both f and ${\widehat {f}}$ are integrable, the inverse equality $f(x)=\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }{\widehat {f}}(\xi )e^{i2\pi x\xi }\,d\xi$ holds for almost every x.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] As a result, the Fourier transform is injective on *L*1(**R**).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Let ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ and ⁠ $g(x)$ ⁠ be integrable, and let ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}$ ⁠ and ⁠ ${\widehat {g}}$ ⁠ be their Fourier transforms.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Plancherel's theorem makes it possible to extend the Fourier transform, by a continuity argument, to a unitary operator on ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Plancherel's theorem has the interpretation in the sciences that the Fourier transform preserves the energy of the original quantity.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The terminology of these formulas is not quite standardised.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Parseval's theorem was proved only for Fourier series, and was first proved by Lyapunov.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] But Parseval's formula makes sense for the Fourier transform as well, and so even though in the context of the Fourier transform it was proved by Plancherel, it is still often referred to as Parseval's formula, or Parseval's relation, or even Parseval's theorem.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] See *Pontryagin duality* for a general formulation of this concept in the context of locally compact abelian groups.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform translates between convolution and multiplication of functions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In linear time invariant (LTI) system theory, it is common to interpret ⁠ $g(x)$ ⁠ as the impulse response of an LTI system with input ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ and output ⁠ $h(x)$ ⁠, since substituting the unit impulse for ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ yields ⁠ $h(x)=g(x)$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In this case, ⁠ ${\widehat {g}}(\xi )$ ⁠ represents the frequency response of the system.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Conversely, if ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ can be decomposed as the product of two square integrable functions ⁠ $p(x)$ ⁠ and ⁠ $q(x)$ ⁠, then the Fourier transform of ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ is given by the convolution of the respective Fourier transforms ⁠ ${\widehat {p}}(\xi )$ ⁠ and ⁠ ${\widehat {q}}(\xi )$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Suppose *f*(*x*) is differentiable almost everywhere, and both ⁠ f ⁠ and its derivative ⁠ $f'$ ⁠ are integrable (in ⁠ $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] By applying the Fourier transform and using these formulas, some ordinary differential equations can be transformed into algebraic equations, which are much easier to solve.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] These formulas also give rise to the rule of thumb "⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ is smooth if and only if ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )$ ⁠ quickly falls to ⁠ 0 ⁠ for ⁠ $\vert \xi \vert \to \infty$ ⁠".
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform is a linear transform that has eigenfunctions obeying ⁠ ${\mathcal {F}}[\psi ]=\lambda \psi$ ⁠, with ⁠ $\lambda \in \mathbb {C}$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In other words, every solution $\psi (x)$ and its Fourier transform ${\widehat {\psi }}(\xi )$ obey the same equation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Assuming uniqueness of the solutions, every solution $\psi (x)$ must therefore be an eigenfunction of the Fourier transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The simplest allowable $U(x)=x$ leads to the standard normal distribution.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The simplest example is provided by ⁠ $W(x)=x^{2}$ ⁠, which is equivalent to considering the Schrödinger equation for the quantum harmonic oscillator.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The corresponding solutions provide an important choice of an orthonormal basis for *L*2(**R**) and are given by the "physicist's" Hermite functions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In other words, the Hermite functions form a complete orthonormal system of eigenfunctions for the Fourier transform on ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] However, this choice of eigenfunctions is not unique.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Because of ${\mathcal {F}}^{4}=\mathrm {id}$ there are only four different eigenvalues of the Fourier transform (the fourth roots of unity ⁠ $\pm 1$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\pm i$ ⁠) and any linear combination of eigenfunctions with the same eigenvalue gives another eigenfunction.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] As a consequence of this, it is possible to decompose *L*2(**R**) as a direct sum of four spaces *H*0, *H*1, *H*2, and *H*3 where the Fourier transform acts on H*k* simply by multiplication by *i**k*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This approach to define the Fourier transform was first proposed by Norbert Wiener.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Among other properties, Hermite functions decrease exponentially fast in both frequency and time domains, and they are thus used to define a generalization of the Fourier transform, namely the fractional Fourier transform used in time–frequency analysis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In physics, this transform was introduced by Edward Condon.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This change of basis becomes possible because the Fourier transform is a unitary transform when using the right conventions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] It can be interpreted as the generator of fractional Fourier transforms for arbitrary values of t, and of the conventional continuous Fourier transform ${\mathcal {F}}$ for the particular value ⁠ $t=\pi /2$ ⁠, with the Mehler kernel implementing the corresponding active transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The eigenfunctions of N are the Hermite functions ⁠ $\psi _{n}(x)$ ⁠, which are therefore also eigenfunctions of ⁠ ${\mathcal {F}}$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Upon extending the Fourier transform to distributions the Dirac comb is also an eigenfunction of the Fourier transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Under suitable conditions on the function ⁠ f ⁠, it can be recovered from its Fourier transform ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In particular the Fourier transform is invertible (under suitable conditions).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] These are not true for all functions, but are true under various conditions, which are the content of the various forms of the Fourier inversion theorem.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This fourfold periodicity of the Fourier transform is similar to a rotation of the plane by 90°, particularly as the two-fold iteration yields a reversal, and in fact this analogy can be made precise.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This can be further generalized to linear canonical transformations, which can be visualized as the action of the special linear group SL2(**R**) on the time–frequency plane, with the preserved symplectic form corresponding to the uncertainty principle, below.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This approach is particularly studied in signal processing, under time–frequency analysis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Heisenberg group is a certain group of unitary operators on the Hilbert space *L*2(**R**) of square integrable complex valued functions f on the real line, generated by the translations (*Ty f*)(*x*) = *f* (*x* + *y*) and multiplication by *e**i*2π*ξx*, (*Mξ f*)(*x*) = *e**i*2π*ξx* *f* (*x*).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] These operators do not commute, as their (group) commutator is $\left(M_{\xi }^{-1}T_{y}^{-1}M_{\xi }T_{y}f\right)(x)=e^{i2\pi \xi y}f(x),$ which is multiplication by the constant (independent of x) *e**i*2π*ξy* ∈ *U*(1) (the circle group of unit modulus complex numbers).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The above procedure describes not only the group structure, but also a standard unitary representation of *H*1 on a Hilbert space, which we denote by *ρ* : *H*1 → *B*(*L*2(**R**)).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Define the linear automorphism of **R**2 by $J{\begin{pmatrix}x\\\xi \end{pmatrix}}={\begin{pmatrix}-\xi \\x\end{pmatrix}}$ so that *J*2 = −*I*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] According to the Stone–von Neumann theorem, the unitary representations ρ and *ρ* ∘ *j* are unitarily equivalent, so there is a unique intertwiner *W* ∈ *U*(*L*2(**R**)) such that $\rho \circ j=W\rho W^{*}.$ This operator W is the Fourier transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Many of the standard properties of the Fourier transform are immediate consequences of this more general framework.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] For example, the square of the Fourier transform, *W*2, is an intertwiner associated with *J*2 = −*I*, and so we have (*W*2*f*)(*x*) = *f* (−*x*) is the reflection of the original function f.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The integral for the Fourier transform ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )=\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }e^{-2i\pi t\xi }f(t)\,dt$ can be studied for complex values of its argument ξ.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Depending on the properties of f, this might not converge off the real axis at all, or it might converge to a complex analytic function for all values of *ξ* = *σ* + *iτ*, or something in between.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] (In this case, f is supported on [−*a*, *a*].) This can be expressed by saying that *f̂* is an entire function that is rapidly decreasing in σ (for fixed τ) and of exponential growth in τ (uniformly in σ).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] (If f is not smooth, but only *L*2, a corresponding version holds with the rapid-decrease condition replaced by the appropriate *L*2 condition.) The space of such functions of a complex variable is called the Paley–Wiener space.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This theorem has been generalised to semisimple Lie groups.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] If f is supported on the half-line *t* ≥ 0, then f is said to be "causal" because the impulse response function of a physically realisable filter must have this property, as no effect can precede its cause.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Paley and Wiener showed that then, under suitable integrability hypotheses, *f̂* extends to a holomorphic function on the complex lower half-plane *τ* < 0 that tends to zero as τ goes to −∞.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] A simple converse in this form is false; precise converses require additional growth or Hardy-space hypotheses.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform *f̂*(*ξ*) is related to the Laplace transform *F*(*s*), which is also used for the solution of differential equations and the analysis of filters.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] It may happen that a function f for which the Fourier integral does not converge on the real axis at all nevertheless has a complex Fourier transform defined in some region of the complex plane.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] If f is causal and the integrals converge, then ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}(i\tau )=F(-2\pi \tau )$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Thus, extending the Fourier transform to the complex domain means it includes the Laplace transform as a special case in the case of causal functions—but with the change of variable *s* = *i*2π*ξ*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] From another, perhaps more classical viewpoint, the Laplace transform by its form involves an additional exponential regulating term that lets it converge outside of the imaginary line where the Fourier transform is defined.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] As such it can converge for functions and integrals with at most exponential growth in the regulated direction, whereas the original Fourier decomposition cannot, enabling analysis of systems with divergent or critical elements.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Two particular examples from linear signal processing are the construction of allpass filter networks from critical comb and mitigating filters via exact pole-zero cancellation on the unit circle.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Such designs are common in audio processing, where highly nonlinear phase response is sought for, as in reverb.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Furthermore, when extended pulselike impulse responses are sought for signal processing work, the easiest way to produce them is to have one circuit that produces a divergent time response, and then to cancel its divergence through a delayed opposite and compensatory response.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] There, only the delay circuit in-between admits a classical Fourier description, which is critical.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Both the circuits to the side are unstable, and do not admit a convergent Fourier decomposition.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] However, they do admit a Laplace domain description, with compatible half-planes of convergence in the complex plane (or in the discrete case, the Z-plane), wherein their effects cancel.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In modern mathematics the Laplace transform is conventionally subsumed under the aegis of Fourier methods.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Both of them are subsumed by the far more general, and more abstract, idea of harmonic analysis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Therefore, the Fourier inversion formula can use integration along different lines, parallel to the real axis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This theorem implies the Mellin inversion formula for the Laplace transformation, $f(t)={\frac {1}{i2\pi }}\int _{b-i\infty }^{b+i\infty }F(s)e^{st}\,ds$ for any *b* > *a*, where *F*(*s*) is the Laplace transform of *f*(*t*).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The hypotheses can be weakened, as in standard Fourier inversion results, to *f*(*t*) *e*−*at* being *L*1, provided that f be of bounded variation in a closed neighborhood of t (cf.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Dini test), the value of f at t be taken to be the arithmetic mean of the left and right limits, and that the integrals be taken in the sense of Cauchy principal values.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform can be defined in any arbitrary number of dimensions n.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] As with the one-dimensional case, there are many conventions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Alternatively, **ξ** can be viewed as belonging to the dual vector space ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n\star }$ ⁠, in which case the dot product becomes the contraction of **x** and **ξ**, usually written as ⟨**x**, **ξ**⟩.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] All of the basic properties listed above hold for the n-dimensional Fourier transform, as do Plancherel's and Parseval's theorem.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] When the function is integrable, the Fourier transform is still uniformly continuous and the Riemann–Lebesgue lemma holds.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Generally speaking, the more concentrated *f*(*x*) is, the more spread out its Fourier transform *f̂*(*ξ*) must be.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In particular, the scaling property of the Fourier transform may be seen as saying: if we squeeze a function in x, its Fourier transform stretches out in ξ.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] It is not possible to arbitrarily concentrate both a function and its Fourier transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Suppose *f*(*x*) is an integrable and square-integrable function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] It follows from the Plancherel theorem that *f̂*(*ξ*) is also normalized.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In probability terms, this is the second moment of |*f*(*x*)|2 about zero.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In other words, where f is a (normalized) Gaussian function with variance *σ*2/2π, centered at zero, and its Fourier transform is a Gaussian function with variance *σ*−2/2π.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Gaussian functions are examples of Schwartz functions (see the discussion on tempered distributions below).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] With this constant properly taken into account, the inequality above becomes the statement of the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The equality is attained for a Gaussian, as in the previous case.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Fourier's original formulation of the transform did not use complex numbers, but rather sines and cosines.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Statisticians and others still use this form.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This is called an expansion as a trigonometric integral, or a Fourier integral expansion.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Older literature refers to the two transform functions, the Fourier cosine transform, a, and the Fourier sine transform, b.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The function f can be recovered from the sine and cosine transform using $f(t)=2\int _{0}^{\infty }\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }f(\tau )\cos {\bigl (}2\pi \lambda (\tau -t){\bigr )}\,d\tau \,d\lambda .$ together with trigonometric identities.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This is referred to as Fourier's integral formula.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Let the set of homogeneous harmonic polynomials of degree k on **R***n* be denoted by **A***k*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The set **A***k* consists of the solid spherical harmonics of degree k.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The solid spherical harmonics play a similar role in higher dimensions to the Hermite polynomials in dimension one.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The space *L*2(**R***n*) is then a direct sum of the spaces **H***k* and the Fourier transform maps each space **H***k* to itself and it is possible to characterize the action of the Fourier transform on each space **H***k*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Here *J*(*n* + 2*k* − 2)/2 denotes the Bessel function of the first kind with order ⁠*n* + 2*k* − 2/2⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] When *k* = 0 this gives a useful formula for the Fourier transform of a radial function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This is essentially the Hankel transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Moreover, there is a simple recursion relating the cases *n* + 2 and n allowing to compute, e.g., the three-dimensional Fourier transform of a radial function from the one-dimensional one.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In higher dimensions it becomes interesting to study *restriction problems* for the Fourier transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform of an integrable function is continuous and the restriction of this function to any set is defined.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] But for a square-integrable function the Fourier transform could be a general *class* of square integrable functions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] As such, the restriction of the Fourier transform of an *L*2(**R***n*) function cannot be defined on sets of measure 0.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] It is still an active area of study to understand restriction problems in *L**p* for 1 < *p* < 2.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] It is possible in some cases to define the restriction of a Fourier transform to a set S, provided S has non-zero curvature.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The case when S is the unit sphere in **R***n* is of particular interest.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In this case the Tomas–Stein restriction theorem states that the restriction of the Fourier transform to the unit sphere in **R***n* is a bounded operator on *L**p* provided 1 ≤ *p* ≤ ⁠2*n* + 2/*n* + 3⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] One notable difference between the Fourier transform in 1 dimension versus higher dimensions concerns the partial sum operator.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Consider an increasing collection of measurable sets *E**R* indexed by *R* ∈ (0, ∞): such as balls of radius R centered at the origin, or cubes of side 2*R*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For *n* = 1 and 1 < *p* < ∞, if one takes *ER* = (−*R*, *R*), then fR converges to f in *L**p* as R tends to infinity, by the boundedness of the Hilbert transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Naively one may hope the same holds true for *n* > 1.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In the case that ER is taken to be a cube with side length R, then convergence still holds.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Another natural candidate is the Euclidean ball *E**R* = {*ξ* : |*ξ*| < *R*}.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In order for this partial sum operator to converge, it is necessary that the multiplier for the unit ball be bounded in *L**p*(**R***n*).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For *n* ≥ 2 it is a celebrated theorem of Charles Fefferman that the multiplier for the unit ball is never bounded unless *p* = 2.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In fact, when *p* ≠ 2, this shows that not only may fR fail to converge to f in *L**p*, but for some functions *f* ∈ *L**p*(**R***n*), fR is not even an element of *L**p*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The definition of the Fourier transform naturally extends from $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ to ⁠ $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Riemann–Lebesgue lemma shows that if $f\in L^{1}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ then its Fourier transform actually belongs to the space of continuous functions that vanish at infinity, i.e., ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}\in C_{0}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})\subset L^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Similarly to the case of one variable, the Fourier transform can be defined on ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform in $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ is no longer given by an ordinary Lebesgue integral, although it can be computed by an improper integral, i.e., ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )=\lim _{R\to \infty }\int _{|x|\leq R}f(x)e^{-i2\pi \xi \cdot x}\,dx$ where the limit is taken in the *L*2 sense.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For an operator to be unitary it is sufficient to show that it is bijective and preserves the inner product.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier inversion theorem implies that the transform is bijective.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] So the transform preserves the inner product.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For ⁠ $1<p<2$ ⁠, the Fourier transform can be defined on $L^{p}(\mathbb {R} )$ by Riesz–Thorin interpolation, which amounts to decomposing such functions into a fat tail part $|f|\leq 1$ in *L*2 plus a fat body part $|f|>1$ in *L*1.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In each of these spaces, the Fourier transform of a function in *L**p*(**R***n*) is in *L**q*(**R***n*), where *q* = ⁠*p*/*p* − 1⁠ is the Hölder conjugate of p (by the Hausdorff–Young inequality).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] However, except for *p* = 2, the image is not easily characterized.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Further extensions become more technical.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform of functions in *L**p* for the range 2 < *p* < ∞ requires the study of distributions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In fact, it can be shown that there are functions in *L**p* with *p* > 2 so that the Fourier transform is not defined as a function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] One might consider enlarging the domain of the Fourier transform from $L^{1}+L^{2}$ by considering generalized functions, or distributions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] A distribution on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is a continuous linear functional on the space $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ of compactly supported smooth functions (i.e. bump functions), equipped with a suitable topology.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Since $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ is dense in ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠, the Plancherel theorem allows one to extend the definition of the Fourier transform to general functions in $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ by continuity arguments.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The strategy is then to consider the action of the Fourier transform on $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ and pass to distributions by duality.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The obstruction to doing this is that the Fourier transform does not map $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ to ⁠ $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In fact the Fourier transform of an element in $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ can not vanish on an open set; see the above discussion on the uncertainty principle.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform can also be defined for tempered distributions ⁠ ${\mathcal {S}}'(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠, dual to the space of Schwartz functions ⁠ ${\mathcal {S}}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The tempered distributions include well-behaved functions of polynomial growth, distributions of compact support as well as all the integrable functions mentioned above.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For the definition of the Fourier transform of a tempered distribution, let f and g be integrable functions, and let ${\widehat {f}}$ and ${\widehat {g}}$ be their Fourier transforms respectively.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Distributions can be differentiated and the above-mentioned compatibility of the Fourier transform with differentiation and convolution remains true for tempered distributions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] If $\mu$ is the probability distribution of a random variable X then its Fourier–Stieltjes transform is, by definition, a characteristic function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] If, in addition, the probability distribution has a probability density function, this definition is subject to the usual Fourier transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Stated more generally, when $\mu$ is absolutely continuous with respect to the Lebesgue measure, i.e., $d\mu =f(x)\,dx,$ then ${\widehat {\mu }}(\xi )={\widehat {f}}(\xi ),$ and the Fourier-Stieltjes transform reduces to the usual definition of the Fourier transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] That is, the notable difference with the Fourier transform of integrable functions is that the Fourier-Stieltjes transform need not vanish at infinity, i.e., the Riemann–Lebesgue lemma fails for measures.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Bochner's theorem characterizes which functions may arise as the Fourier–Stieltjes transform of a positive measure on the circle.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] One example of a finite Borel measure that is not a function is the Dirac measure.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Its Fourier transform is a constant function (whose value depends on the form of the Fourier transform used).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform may be generalized to any locally compact abelian group, i.e., an abelian group that is also a locally compact Hausdorff space such that the group operation is continuous.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] If G is a locally compact abelian group, it has a translation invariant measure μ, called Haar measure.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For a locally compact abelian group G, the set of irreducible, i.e. one-dimensional, unitary representations are called its characters.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Riemann–Lebesgue lemma holds in this case; *f̂*(*ξ*) is a function vanishing at infinity on Ĝ.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform on T = R/Z is an example; here T is a locally compact abelian group, and the Haar measure μ on T can be thought of as the Lebesgue measure on [0,1).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Consider a representation of T on the complex plane C thought of as a 1-dimensional complex vector space.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] There is a group of such representations (which are irreducible since C is 1-dim) $\{e_{k}:T\rightarrow GL_{1}(C)=C^{*}\mid k\in Z\}$ where $e_{k}(x)=e^{i2\pi kx}$ for ⁠ $x\in T$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The character of such representation, that is the trace of $e_{k}(x)$ (thought of as a one-by-one matrix) for each $x\in T$ and ⁠ $k\in Z$ ⁠, is $e^{i2\pi kx}$ itself.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The group T is no longer finite but still compact, and it preserves the orthonormality of the character table.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The sequence $\{e_{k}\mid k\in Z\}$ is an orthonormal basis of the space of class functions ⁠ $L^{2}(T,d\mu )$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform is also a special case of the Gelfand transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In this particular context, it is closely related to the Pontryagin duality map defined above.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Given an abelian locally compact Hausdorff topological group G, as before we consider the space *L*1(*G*), defined using a Haar measure.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] With convolution as multiplication, *L*1(*G*) is an abelian Banach algebra.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Taking the completion with respect to the largest possible *C**-norm gives its enveloping *C**-algebra, called the group *C**-algebra *C**(*G*) of G.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Given any abelian *C**-algebra A, the Gelfand transform gives an isomorphism between A and *C*0(*A*^), where *A*^ is the multiplicative linear functionals, i.e. one-dimensional representations, on A with the weak-* topology.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform can also be defined for functions on a non-abelian group, provided that the group is compact.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Removing the assumption that the underlying group is abelian, irreducible unitary representations need not always be one-dimensional.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This means the Fourier transform on a non-abelian group takes values as Hilbert space operators.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform on compact groups is a major tool in representation theory and non-commutative harmonic analysis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Let G be a compact Hausdorff topological group, and let λ be its normalized Haar measure.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Let Σ denote the collection of all isomorphism classes of finite-dimensional irreducible unitary representations, along with a definite choice of representation *U*(*σ*) on the Hilbert space *Hσ* of finite dimension *dσ* for each *σ* ∈ Σ.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The involution on *M*(*G*) is given, for absolutely continuous measures, by $f^{*}(g)={\overline {f(g^{-1})}},$ since compact groups are unimodular.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Peter–Weyl theorem holds, and a version of the Fourier inversion formula follows: if *f* ∈ *L*2(*G*), then $f(g)=\sum _{\sigma \in \Sigma }d_{\sigma }\operatorname {tr} \left({\widehat {f}}(\sigma )U_{g}^{(\sigma )}\right),$ where the summation is understood as convergent in the *L*2 sense.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The generalization of the Fourier transform to the noncommutative situation has also in part contributed to the development of noncommutative geometry.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In this context, a categorical generalization of the Fourier transform to noncommutative groups is Tannaka–Krein duality, which replaces the group of characters with the category of representations.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] However, this is no longer simply a transform of scalar-valued functions into scalar-valued functions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This limits the usefulness of the Fourier transform for analyzing signals that are localized in time, notably transients, or any signal of finite extent.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] As alternatives to the Fourier transform, in time–frequency analysis, one uses time–frequency transforms or time–frequency distributions to represent signals in a form that has some time information and some frequency information – by the uncertainty principle, there is a trade-off between these.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The following figures provide a visual illustration of how the Fourier transform's integral measures whether a frequency is present in a particular function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The first image depicts the function ⁠ $f(t)=\cos(2\pi \ 3t)\ e^{-\pi t^{2}}$ ⁠, which is a 3 Hz cosine wave (the first term) shaped by a Gaussian envelope function (the second term) that smoothly turns the wave on and off.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The next 2 images show the product ⁠ $f(t)e^{-i2\pi 3t}$ ⁠, which must be integrated to calculate the Fourier transform at +3 Hz.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The real part of the integrand has a non-negative average value, because the alternating signs of $f(t)$ and $\operatorname {Re} (e^{-i2\pi 3t})$ oscillate at the same rate and in phase, whereas $f(t)$ and $\operatorname {Im} (e^{-i2\pi 3t})$ oscillate at the same rate but with orthogonal phase.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The absolute value of the Fourier transform at +3 Hz is 0.5, which is relatively large.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] When added to the Fourier transform at -3 Hz (which is identical because we started with a real signal), we find that the amplitude of the 3 Hz frequency component is 1.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] However, when you try to measure a frequency that is not present, both the real and imaginary component of the integral vary rapidly between positive and negative values.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For instance, the red curve is looking for 5 Hz.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The absolute value of its integral is nearly zero, indicating that almost no 5 Hz component was in the signal.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The general situation is usually more complicated than this, but heuristically this is how the Fourier transform measures how much of an individual frequency is present in a function ⁠ $f(t)$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] To re-enforce an earlier point, the reason for the response at $\xi =-3$ Hz is because $\cos(2\pi 3t)$ and $\cos(2\pi (-3)t)$ are indistinguishable.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Linear operations performed in one domain (time or frequency) have corresponding operations in the other domain, which are sometimes easier to perform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The operation of differentiation in the time domain corresponds to multiplication by the frequency, so some differential equations are easier to analyze in the frequency domain.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Also, convolution in the time domain corresponds to ordinary multiplication in the frequency domain (see *Convolution theorem*).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] After performing the desired operations, transformation of the result can be made back to the time domain.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Harmonic analysis is the systematic study of the relationship between the frequency and time domains, including the kinds of functions or operations that are "simpler" in one or the other, and has deep connections to many areas of modern mathematics.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Perhaps the most important use of the Fourier transformation is to solve partial differential equations.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Many of the equations of the mathematical physics of the nineteenth century can be treated this way.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] As usual, the problem is not to find a solution: there are infinitely many.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] For the heat equation, only one boundary condition can be required (usually the first one).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] But for the wave equation, there are still infinitely many solutions y that satisfy the first boundary condition.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] But when one imposes both conditions, there is only one possible solution.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] It is easier to find the Fourier transform ŷ of the solution than to find the solution directly.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] After ŷ is determined, we can apply the inverse Fourier transformation to find y.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] First, note that any function of the forms $\cos {\bigl (}2\pi \xi (x\pm t){\bigr )}{\text{ or }}\sin {\bigl (}2\pi \xi (x\pm t){\bigr )}$ satisfies the wave equation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] These are called the elementary solutions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This integral may be interpreted as a continuous linear combination of solutions for the linear equation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Now this resembles the formula for the Fourier synthesis of a function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In fact, this is the real inverse Fourier transform of *a*± and *b*± in the variable x.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The third step is to examine how to find the specific unknown coefficient functions *a*± and *b*± that will lead to y satisfying the boundary conditions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] We are interested in the values of these solutions at *t* = 0.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] These are four linear equations for the four unknowns *a*± and *b*±, in terms of the Fourier sine and cosine transforms of the boundary conditions, which are easily solved by elementary algebra, provided that these transforms can be found.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In summary, we chose a set of elementary solutions, parametrized by ξ, of which the general solution would be a (continuous) linear combination in the form of an integral over the parameter ξ.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] But this integral was in the form of a Fourier integral.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The next step was to express the boundary conditions in terms of these integrals, and set them equal to the given functions f and g.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] But these expressions also took the form of a Fourier integral because of the properties of the Fourier transform of a derivative.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The last step was to exploit Fourier inversion by applying the Fourier transformation to both sides, thus obtaining expressions for the coefficient functions *a*± and *b*± in terms of the given boundary conditions f and g.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] From a higher point of view, Fourier's procedure can be reformulated more conceptually.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Since there are two variables, we will use the Fourier transformation in both x and t rather than operate as Fourier did, who only transformed in the spatial variables.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Note that ŷ must be considered in the sense of a distribution since *y*(*x*, *t*) is not going to be *L*1: as a wave, it will persist through time and thus is not a transient phenomenon.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] But it will be bounded and so its Fourier transform can be defined as a distribution.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The operational properties of the Fourier transformation that are relevant to this equation are that it takes differentiation in x to multiplication by *i*2π*ξ* and differentiation with respect to t to multiplication by *i*2π*f* where f is the frequency.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Then the wave equation becomes an algebraic equation in ŷ: $\xi ^{2}{\widehat {y}}(\xi ,f)=f^{2}{\widehat {y}}(\xi ,f).$ This is equivalent to requiring *ŷ*(*ξ*, *f*) = 0 unless *ξ* = ±*f*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Right away, this explains why the choice of elementary solutions we made earlier worked so well: obviously *ŷ* = *δ*(*ξ* ± *f*) will be solutions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Applying Fourier inversion to these delta functions, we obtain the elementary solutions we picked earlier.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] But from the higher point of view, one does not pick elementary solutions, but rather considers the space of all distributions that are supported on the (degenerate) conic *ξ*2 − *f*2 = 0.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Now, as before, applying the one-variable Fourier transformation in the variable x to these functions of x yields two equations in the two unknown distributions *s*± (which can be taken to be ordinary functions if the boundary conditions are *L*1 or *L*2).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] From a calculational point of view, the drawback of course is that one must first calculate the Fourier transforms of the boundary conditions, then assemble the solution from these, and then calculate an inverse Fourier transform.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Closed form formulas are rare, except when there is some geometric symmetry that can be exploited, and the numerical calculations are difficult because of the oscillatory nature of the integrals, which makes convergence slow and hard to estimate.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] For practical calculations, other methods are often used.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The twentieth century has seen application of these methods to all linear partial differential equations with polynomial coefficients as well as an extension to certain classes of nonlinear partial differential equations.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Specifically, nonlinear evolution equations (i.e. those equations that describe how a particular quantity evolves in time from a specified initial state) that can be associated with linear eigenvalue problems whose eigenvalues are integrals of the nonlinear equations.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] As it may be considered an extension of Fourier analysis to nonlinear problems, the solution method is called the **nonlinear Fourier transform** (or **inverse scattering transform**) method.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform is also used in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) and in other kinds of spectroscopy, e.g. infrared (FTIR).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In NMR an exponentially shaped free induction decay (FID) signal is acquired in the time domain and Fourier-transformed to a Lorentzian line-shape in the frequency domain.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform is also used in magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and mass spectrometry.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform is useful in quantum mechanics in at least two different ways.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] To begin with, the basic conceptual structure of quantum mechanics postulates the existence of pairs of complementary variables, connected by the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] For example, in one dimension, the spatial variable q of, say, a particle, can only be measured by the quantum mechanical "position operator" at the cost of losing information about the momentum p of the particle.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Therefore, the physical state of the particle can either be described by a function, called "the wave function", of q or by a function of p but not by a function of both variables.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The variable p is called the conjugate variable to q.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In classical mechanics, the physical state of a particle (existing in one dimension, for simplicity of exposition) would be given by assigning definite values to both p and q simultaneously.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Thus, the set of all possible physical states is the two-dimensional real vector space with a p-axis and a q-axis called the phase space.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In contrast, quantum mechanics chooses a polarisation of this space in the sense that it picks a subspace of one-half the dimension, for example, the q-axis alone, but instead of considering only points, takes the set of all complex-valued "wave functions" on this axis.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Nevertheless, choosing the p-axis is an equally valid polarisation, yielding a different representation of the set of possible physical states of the particle.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Physically realisable states are *L*2, and so by the Plancherel theorem, their Fourier transforms are also *L*2.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Therefore, the Fourier transform can be used to pass from one way of representing the state of the particle, by a wave function of position, to another way of representing the state of the particle: by a wave function of momentum.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Infinitely many different polarisations are possible, and all are equally valid.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Being able to transform states from one representation to another by the Fourier transform is not only convenient but also the underlying reason of the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The other use of the Fourier transform in both quantum mechanics and quantum field theory is to solve the applicable wave equation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This is the same as the heat equation except for the presence of the imaginary unit i.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Fourier methods can be used to solve this equation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The "elementary solutions", as we referred to them above, are the so-called "stationary states" of the particle, and Fourier's algorithm, as described above, can still be used to solve the boundary value problem of the future evolution of ψ given its values for *t* = 0.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Neither of these approaches is of much practical use in quantum mechanics.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Boundary value problems and the time-evolution of the wave function is not of much practical interest: it is the stationary states that are most important.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In relativistic quantum mechanics, the Schrödinger equation becomes a wave equation as was usual in classical physics, except that complex-valued waves are considered.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This is, from the mathematical point of view, the same as the wave equation of classical physics solved above (but with a complex-valued wave, which makes no difference in the methods).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This is of great use in quantum field theory: each separate Fourier component of a wave can be treated as a separate harmonic oscillator and then quantized, a procedure known as "second quantization".
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Fourier methods have been adapted to also deal with non-trivial interactions.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Finally, the number operator of the quantum harmonic oscillator can be interpreted, for example via the Mehler kernel, as the generator of the Fourier transform ⁠ ${\mathcal {F}}$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform is used for the spectral analysis of time-series.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The subject of statistical signal processing does not, however, usually apply the Fourier transformation to the signal itself.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Even if a real signal is indeed transient, it has been found in practice advisable to model a signal by a function (or, alternatively, a stochastic process) that is stationary in the sense that its characteristic properties are constant over all time.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform of such a function does not exist in the usual sense, and it has been found more useful for the analysis of signals to instead take the Fourier transform of its autocorrelation function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This function is a function of the time-lag τ elapsing between the values of f to be correlated.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] For most functions f that occur in practice, R is a bounded even function of the time-lag τ and for typical noisy signals it turns out to be uniformly continuous with a maximum at *τ* = 0.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The autocorrelation function, more properly called the autocovariance function unless it is normalized in some appropriate fashion, measures the strength of the correlation between the values of f separated by a time lag.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This is a way of searching for the correlation of f with its own past.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] It is useful even for other statistical tasks besides the analysis of signals.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] For example, if *f*(*t*) represents the temperature at time t, one expects a strong correlation with the temperature at a time lag of 24 hours.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This Fourier transform is called the power spectral density function of f.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The power spectrum, as indicated by this density function P, measures the amount of variance contributed to the data by the frequency ξ.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In electrical signals, the variance is proportional to the average power (energy per unit time), and so the power spectrum describes how much the different frequencies contribute to the average power of the signal.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This process is called the spectral analysis of time-series and is analogous to the usual analysis of variance of data that is not a time-series (ANOVA).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Knowledge of which frequencies are "important" in this sense is crucial for the proper design of filters and for the proper evaluation of measuring apparatuses.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] It can also be useful for the scientific analysis of the phenomena responsible for producing the data.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The power spectrum of a signal can also be approximately measured directly by measuring the average power that remains in a signal after all the frequencies outside a narrow band have been filtered out.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Spectral analysis is carried out for visual signals as well.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The power spectrum ignores all phase relations, which is good enough for many purposes, but for video signals other types of spectral analysis must also be employed, still using the Fourier transform as a tool.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] A disadvantage of the capital letter notation is when expressing a transform such as ${\widehat {f}}\cdot g$ or ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}'$ ⁠, which become the more awkward ${\mathcal {F}}\{f\cdot g\}$ and ⁠ ${\mathcal {F}}\{f'\}$ ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Although tildes may be used as in ${\tilde {f}}$ to indicate Fourier transforms, tildes may also be used to indicate a modification of a quantity with a more Lorentz invariant form, such as ⁠ ${\tilde {dk}}={\frac {dk}{(2\pi )^{3}2\omega }}$ ⁠, so care must be taken.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Similarly, ${\widehat {f}}$ often denotes the Hilbert transform of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Then the inverse transform can be written: $f(x)=\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }A(\xi )\ e^{i{\bigl (}2\pi \xi x+\varphi (\xi ){\bigr )}}\,d\xi ,$ which is a recombination of all the frequency components of *f*(*x*).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Each component is a complex sinusoid of the form *e*2π*ixξ* whose amplitude is *A*(*ξ*) and whose initial phase angle (at *x* = 0) is *φ*(*ξ*).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform may be thought of as a mapping on function spaces.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This mapping is here denoted F and F(*f*) is used to denote the Fourier transform of the function f.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This mapping is linear, which means that F can also be seen as a linear transformation on the function space and implies that the standard notation in linear algebra of applying a linear transformation to a vector (here the function *f*) can be used to write F *f* instead of F(*f*).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Since the result of applying the Fourier transform is again a function, we can be interested in the value of this function evaluated at the value ξ for its variable, and this is denoted either as F *f*(*ξ*) or as (F *f*)(*ξ*).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Notice that in the former case, it is implicitly understood that F is applied first to f and then the resulting function is evaluated at ξ, not the other way around.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In mathematics and various applied sciences, it is often necessary to distinguish between a function f and the value of f when its variable equals x, denoted *f*(*x*).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This means that a notation like F(*f*(*x*)) formally can be interpreted as the Fourier transform of the values of f at x.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Despite this flaw, the previous notation appears frequently, often when a particular function or a function of a particular variable is to be transformed.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Notice, that the last example is only correct under the assumption that the transformed function is a function of x, not of *x*0.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] As discussed above, the characteristic function of a random variable is the same as the Fourier–Stieltjes transform of its distribution measure, but in this context it is typical to take a different convention for the constants.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] As in the case of the "non-unitary angular frequency" convention above, the factor of 2π appears in neither the normalizing constant nor the exponent.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Unlike any of the conventions appearing above, this convention takes the opposite sign in the exponent.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The appropriate computation method largely depends how the original mathematical function is represented and the desired form of the output function.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In this section we consider both functions of a continuous variable, ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠, and functions of a discrete variable (i.e. ordered pairs of x and f values).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] For discrete-valued ⁠ x ⁠, the transform integral becomes a summation of sinusoids, which is still a continuous function of frequency (⁠ $\xi$ ⁠ or ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] When the sinusoids are harmonically related (i.e. when the x -values are spaced at integer multiples of an interval), the transform is called discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Sampling the DTFT at equally-spaced values of frequency is the most common modern method of computation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Efficient procedures, depending on the frequency resolution needed, are described at Discrete-time Fourier transform § Sampling the DTFT.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The discrete Fourier transform (DFT), used there, is usually computed by a fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithm.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] When mathematically possible, this provides a transform for a continuum of frequency values.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Discrete sampling of the Fourier transform can also be done by numerical integration of the definition at each value of frequency for which transform is desired.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The numerical integration approach works on a much broader class of functions than the analytic approach.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] If the input function is a series of ordered pairs, numerical integration reduces to just a summation over the set of data pairs.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The DTFT is a common subcase of this more general situation.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p04] The following tables record some closed-form Fourier transforms.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p04] For functions *f*(*x*) and *g*(*x*) denote their Fourier transforms by *f̂* and *ĝ*.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p04] Only the three most common conventions are included.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p04] It may be useful to notice that entry 105 gives a relationship between the Fourier transform of a function and the original function, which can be seen as relating the Fourier transform and its inverse.
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p04] The Fourier transforms in this table may be found in Erdélyi (1954) or Kammler (2000, appendix).
[src:fourier-analysis/fourier-transform-p04] The Fourier transforms in this table may be found in Campbell & Foster (1948), Erdélyi (1954), or Kammler (2000, appendix).
